9 of 9 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsNot an iPad, but good for what it is,March 29, 2012By&nbsp;ifgriffi-See all my reviewsThis review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Let's get this out of the way: the Fire is in most ways a compromise product. If you have a bit more to spend and are looking for a more full-featured device, consider a refurb iPad 2 for $349 from Apple, as well as a number of brand-name 10-inch Android devices in the same price range. If you're on a budget though, the Fire is a nice tablet that's worth taking a look at.The Kindle Fire runs a custom version of the Android operating system. The interface Amazon has built consists of a "carousel" that displays all of the content you have used recently, with tabs along the top to navigate through the various types of content on the device. This works reasonably well, though the carousel can get cluttered. Overall, navigation feels a little bit laggy; the carousel sometimes stutters, and it sometimes takes a second to refresh when you quit an application. It's not a big deal, but it is noticeable.The e-reader functionality works about as expected. Obviously this is a back-lit LCD display, so it isn't as easy on the eyes as an e-ink reader. Kindle formatted books look good, but the small screen means a lot of pinching and zooming on PDFs. Video playback looks very acceptable, and if you have Prime membership you get access to a large selection of videos to watch for free. I was very excited about the Kindle lending library before getting this, but unless you're a fan of romance novels and self-help books the selection is pretty thin. If you don't mind waiting, a lot of public libraries have Kindle books that can be checked out online. The Fire can run Android apps, but out of the box the only way to get them is to use the Amazon App Store. Most of the major apps are on here, and they give away a paid app for free every day, but the selection is not as broad as on the Google Play store. Most games come in special "Kindle Fire" versions, which are formatted for the Fire's screen but cost a couple of dollars more than the standard version for no discernible reason. It's annoying, but the prices are still pretty reasonable.The Fire isn't going to blow anyone away with its specs, but its dual-core processor and 512 megs of RAM are more than decent given its price point. It has 8gb of built in storage, which hasn't been an issue for me but if you plan on loading it up with a bunch of videos you'll probably fill it up pretty quickly. As mentioned above, navigation feels a bit laggy. The much-vaunted Silk browser unfortunately also feels not-so-quick. Surprisingly, 3D games fare much better. Games like Dead Space and Shine Runner look really good and play smoothly. It's not going to give $500 tablets a run for their money, but for a $199 device it's hard to complain.One thing to keep in mind is that the Fire comes out of the box tied to your Amazon account with 1-click ordering enabled. This is neat, and if it is for personal use it won't be a huge problem. However, it is something to be aware of if you're thinking of letting kids or others use it. Given that they've been pushing this as a "my first tablet", I'm surprised that they didn't do a better job of making it kid-friendly. It seems like a missed opportunity.If you can swing the extra cost for a 10-inch tablet, the additional screen size will make your experience better. If your budget is $200, the Fire is probably the best you can do (barring the occasional super sale). If nothing else, you can be assured access to a ton of Amazon content and continuing software support (they have released 3 software updates already). At the time I write this, Amazon is offering a refurbished Fire for $139, which makes it an absolute no-brainer.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (2)

