11 of 12 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsAmazing and solid device with some caveats but perfect price point,November 23, 2011By&nbsp;R. Santo Tomas(Pacifica, CA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)The $199 price point was pretty compelling, I thought. Surfs the web, magazines/books, email, and Android apps plus Angry Birds? Sold.I received the Kindle Fire the day after scheduled release.The device is solidly built. It fits in one hand much like a paperback would and in line with previous Kindle models. The device comes plainly packaged with the Fire and a USB recharging power adapter.It boots up after about a minute and required an update after I had registered the device. The walk-through of the wireless setup was simple enough. Remember, that this device offers no 3G so you need to have a wireless connection if you want internet access.It has a modest but serviceable 8 GB of memory with only a little over 6 GB that is actually usable. The screen is quite nice but is highly reflective much like the iPad so unlike other Kindles, don't think about using this thing if there is glare from behind. The weight feels a tad hefty for its size but never cumbersome or fatiguing to holdMuch like the iPad is not quite a giant iPhone; the Fire isn't quite a giant Android phone either. That is both good and bad. It doesn't have a camera - which I frankly have no need for. It also uses an Amazon custom interface that is put on top of the Android OS. It is missing some welcome features like an SD slot.The Home page isn't your collection of apps as you may expect. Instead, it's 'recent apps/books' along with a collection of Favorites that you can setup. Considering that I wil go back to the Home page quite often, I would have preferred simply having all my Apps in one full page.I connected the device to a MacBook Pro and it mounted like any other external hard drive. There are obvious folders to place movies, pictures, etc.  Less clear is where to put other files such as PDFs.Email works as advertised. Nothing amazing but more than serviceable. I did, however, have to download a separate application in order to get Exchange email server working. I would have loved to have this application included as I see many people using this for work purposes as I am. Once setup, however, all my emails and contacts synced without a hitch.The 7" screen may be a showstopper for some as text can often be quite small unless you zoom in. I found that books fared better than say magazines (depending on the publication) because fonts seem to be more consistent. I also used the Comic Book application to check out some DC and Marvel offerings. Those worked about as well as I could have hoped though I am disappointed that Amazon has yet to create a partnership with comic publishers to provide subscription models as they do with magazines.Navigation is mostly easy. I say mostly because you often have to go to the Home page before being able to access the different pages of the Fire: Apps, Books, Web, etc.  There is no easy way to jump from page to page without going Home first.I did some streaming of some Amazon videos and they looked great. The same can be said of the personal pictures that I have put in the Fire. I don't really plan to use it for music much but that works well enough as well.There are a surprising number of Android apps that you essentially download from the Amazon application that are readily available. I downloaded WORDS and Angry Birds along with a few apps for Chat. I use Quickoffice for basic MS Office compatibility for Excel and Word. You can download Adobe Reader or simply use the provided Kindle reader for pdfs. Once you register your device, you can send yourself documents via email and they will be pushed to your device via [yourname]@kindle.comYou may think that I am being overly critical but I'm not. I realize that this not have to compete with the iPad 2. At about 1/3 the price point, it doesn't need to. It has its hiccups but everything that should work - does. The only caveat is that it isn't as smooth or as graceful as I would like especially since the barriers are merely design choices in the software as opposed to hardware limitations.I hate to overemphasize the price but it really is an awesome device for the price point that it is being offered. I'm keeping it and recommending to a broad number of people that want to get into the tablet market without plopping $500.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

