7 of 7 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsReview from a college student,December 13, 2011By&nbsp;E. Luna "FPS Connoisseur"(Austin, Tx)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I've had the kindle fire for a little bit less than a week now, and I have to say that I am mightily impressed with the quality of this product. In the span of a week this device has literally become an indispensable tool for studying and for some off the cuff fun as well. I am currently in finals week in my university, and my Kindle has allowed me to study while I am on the bus without having to take put my unwieldy laptop from my backpack. In fact I have largely neglected my laptop while I am on campus. The ability to have all my .pdf and .doc files readily available for me to read is something liberating for me. I am studying in a big university so almost everything that is handed out by professors is electronic in an effort to alleviate the dependency on paper handouts. As I write this I am reading all the necessary books and notes for my English final. The Fire is a primarily a media hub for Amazons extensive library of movies, apps, magazines, and books. In a way, the Fire was created to accommodate nearly all of the services that Amazon offers for prime members under one roof. Having Netflix, and the Amazon video service gives me a plethora of videos that I can choose from. As soon as I received my Kindle I downloaded "The Hunger Games" as part of the Kindle lending library. I am thoroughly impressed with the reader program that the Kindle offers. Make no mistake, the e-ink is obviously better than a back lit display, but nonetheless the Kindle Fire gets the job done admirably. In my opinion the 7" display is just right for this type of product. It allows for portability and easy-access when in a tight room. It's also big enough to be convenient when surfing the web or reading a book. I use glasses, so my vision is far from perfect, but I have no difficulty reading the text on the Kindle. Speaking of surfing the web, the Silk browser is spectacular. At first it may seem to be a little slow, comparable to the browser on my Droid X, but with constant usage, my most visited sites load in a pinch. This, in essence, is the point of the Silk browser. It picks up on repeated usage and it pre-loads websites that are constantly used by you. Given more time, I'm sure that the Silk will continue to improve its performance. One of the benefits of being in a big campus is that I am literally on wi-fi nearly all the time. Watching videos on the Fire is also something that is easy and fast. As of my purchase I have seen a few episodes of American Dad on Netflix and a plethora of videos on YouTube. Every single time I have had a wonderful experience. Some consumers have gripes regarding the hardware itself. The power button being on the bottom makes it easy to accidentally turn of the Fire. The lack of physical volume buttons. Some even complain that the Kindle fire is to plain looking. First off the power button issue can be resolved by holding the fire upside down. No, I'm not crazy. The screen adjusts itself to however you are holding the device. The volume buttons issue is not a deal breaker in any way whatsoever, because lowering or raising the volume is easily done through the quick-settings tab that can be accessed by tapping on the gear in the upper right hand corner. As far as the device itself, I love the design. I love simple, elegant devices that  are not garish or tacky. The back is made of a slightly rubberized material that is easy to grip on to. The only thing that is embossed on the back is the word "kindle" and an amazon branding is printed on the lower end. The screen is vibrant and bright, and it is made with gorilla-glass so scratching the device won't be easy unless you deliberately are trying to do so.On to the memory space. The kindle has about 6.5 gigs of available memory. It's not a lot, but the cloud service that is included with the device is downright impressive. It is so easy to download books, apps, or movies that are saved in the cloud. In a way you have unlimited space on your Kindle Fire through the Amazon cloud service.For the price this product is amazing, phenomenal, stunning, and a true bargain. For those of you who love tinkering with your devices, you can root the Fire and make it run just like a normal Android tablet. I, myself, am an "out of the box" customer, so I tend not to mess around with the software like that but it's nice to have that option. So as a college student, I give the Fire two very enthusiastic thumbs up!Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

7 of 7 people found the following review helpful2.0 out of 5 starsI might return mine. Definitely NOT for parents with kids.,December 12, 2011By&nbsp;Sam Johnson(Florida, USA)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I really wanted to like the Fire and it's not horrible for 1.0 product, still, I might return mine. It's just not what it needs to be and is actually a hazard to leave around the house if you have kids.  By "hazard" I don't mean that it can break and hurt your child.  I just mean content wise there are no parental controls and lots of opportunities for kids to view things that many parents don't want their young kids to see. I'm not trying to sound prudish, but in addition to it's many other flaws it doesn't seem like a good idea for Adults and Children to both use this device. I'll explain a bit more below.But first, the Fire might be worth it if...- You have Amazon Prime and no kids. I have an iPad which I love.  But I can't access any of Amazon Prime's video content on it because there is no Flash support. The Kindle Fire does allow you access that content well and I enjoy it for that. If you don't have a Prime account, honestly I don't think it's worth the money.  So unless you are willing to pay $80 a year for Prime, then I wouldn't get the Kindle Fire.Don't Buy it if...you have kids.- I have kids and I don't want them to touch this thing by themselves.  Why? There are many reasons:No parental controls that I can find. Kids can view racy videos and racy book covers from Amazon pages. Could they do this in theory on my iPad. Yes, probably.  But the kids would have to go out on the web, go to Amazon, navigate the site to get to the right pages, they would have to know my password, etc. But with this Kindle Fire, everything is right there and easily to find.  Plus,whatever you look at immediately shows up on the front "carousel" and there is NO WAY to delete it that I can find (at least not at the time of writing this review). So that means if my wife picks this up and decides to watch an "R" rated movie, let's say, it now appears in the carousel and the next day if the kids pick this up they see this movie front and center and may think, "Hey, what's this?" and start watching it.Sure, you may be thinking.  Then just keep it away from the kids.  Yes, I can and am doing just that. But one of the whole selling points of the Fire (at least in the initial review I read), was that this low cost device is perfect for kids because of the low cost and thus lower worry level for parents if they drop it or mess it up somehow.  And Amazon is clearly targeting this device for use by kids, with everything from kids books, to games, to learning apps. I wouldn't be surprised if they even advertised it as a perfect device for parents who have iPads, but don't want their kids on the iPad so they can get this lower cost Amazon device for the kiddies to use. I wouldn't recommend that.  There are just too many ways for kids to find stuff they probably shouldn't and no useful parental controls that I can find.Here are a few other nit-pick dislikes:- No external volume control. This makes the device a huge hassle in many situations. And even though you get used to it after awhile, the annoyance factor never goes away.- Small "touch screen" elements. Here's the thing, I don't have a problem with the small screen size, what really is annoying is that so many things on the screen that you have to touch are so small.  I suppose this could be fixed with a software update--and I hope it will.  But right now there are many little "buttons" you can touch that are so small that I often have "tap" errors (i.e. pressing the wrong thing).  This really needs to be fixed.- Really limited number of apps. I'm sure this will improve over time, but right now there are really only a handful of apps worth owning.- Web browsing experience is SLOW. You know, after seeing the Amazon promotion video about the "Silk" browser and how speedy it was I had high expectations. Great idea, I thought. Ummm, not so much. This is really slow browsing. If this is what Silk can do, I'd rather pass and download Google Chrome...but Amazon doesn't give you an option to use any browser but their own.- Touch screen trouble. About half the time I have to touch the touch screen more than once (or twice) to get something to activate.  It's just annoying and frustrating.  The weird thing is, it isn't consistent.  In other words, some days the touch screen seems to work pretty well, other days it's rather unresponsive. Don't know if this is a hardware or software thing. Hopefully software so they can fix it with an update.In the end, I just don't think I can recommend this to people to buy.  Especially not for parents.  Right now, I can't decide if I'm going to keep it or not. Since I do have Prime, I might keep it.  But here's the truth.  If I had had the chance to actually USE the Kindle Fire for a week or two before making my buying decision I wouldn't have bought it. It's just not ready for Prime-time yet.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (2)

