7 of 7 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsNook vs Fire - an honest review from an ereader fan,December 8, 2011By&nbsp;tfremon-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I wanted to share my thoughts comparing the Nook Color and the Kindle Fire.  I am an average housewife looking for a good book and a game every now and then.  I was not wanting a "tablet", just an ereader with more capabilites than reading books.  This summer I purchased a Nook Color and I preordered the Kindle Fire.  I wanted to compare them and whichever one I liked best I would keep.  The loser would go to my kids.After using both, I have decided the kids will get the...Nook Color.  But I might add, that I believe the Nook Color was the best choice for my kids also. For the following reasons:I love the Nook Color childrens books.  They are interactive and keep my kids attention (ages 4, 6 and 9).Most importantly, they have parental controls for downloads.  The Fire lacks parental controls, therefore only getting 4 stars.  My 4 yr old has already figured out how to order apps on the fire, to my dismay.  The nook color also has great apps for children, although a lot of them you have to pay for, whereas, you can find many of the apps on the Fire for free.The Fire weighs less than the Nook Color.  I believe the Nook tablet weighs even less than the Fire.  I don't have an e-ink reader, so I had nothing to compare the weight issue to.  I can hold both the Nook and Fire easily and I can hold them for hours reading books on them.  In my opinion, the weight is a non-issue to me.The Fire was the best choice for me over the Nook Color for the following reasons:1.  Smaller in size.  It is nice for me because I don't carry a big purse and it fits nicely in there.2.  Wi-Fi.  It is a tie between the Nook and Fire.  I don't need 3g because my intent was not to be able to browse the internet from anywhere.  I would get a smart phone if I wanted that.  The wi-fi suits me just fine.  Although on the fire, it tends to loose its signal more in my home than the Nook did.3.  Keyboard:  I like the keyboard a little better on the Fire.  It is easier to tap and with auto correction, it makes typing emails a breeze.  If I had to type a long email or document, like this review, I prefer the standard keyboard on my laptop.  But with the need for minimal typing the keyboard on the Fire works great.4.  Apps:  By far the winner is the Fire.  It has great apps and many I have found are cheap.  I am not a professional and need a lot of utility apps.  I just mainly browse the games, both for myself and my children.  I have found that many I had to pay for on the Nook, were free on the Kindle.5.  Streaming:  I tried to stream one video on the Nook.  It didn't go so well...it had lots of hangups and was very choppy.  Although I really don't stream a lot, the Fire does a much better job of that. I have also downloaded a couple tv shows to keep on my kindle in case my kids get restless at the doctors office, store, etc.  That comes in handy quite a bit.6.  Music:  I don't really download music so I don't have any comments on this area.  I do, however, have the pandora app and listen to music that way.  Works about the same on the Nook and Fire.7.  Speakers:  This is one area the fire lags.  Both speakers are located on the bottom and when you are watching a movie, all the sounds come from the left or right side.  But it is not a problem if you use earbuds.8.  Amazon Prime:  I am disappointed with the free shows or movies amazon offers for their Prime members.  My kids wanted to watch Edward Scissorhands, which was made YEARS ago, and I had to pay to rent it.  It was not offered to Prime members, which was disappointing.  But I do love prime for the book lending.  I noticed they had a Chelsea Handler book that I paid $13 for to read on my Nook, and I could have read it for free on the Prime book lending program they have.  The free shipping is also great, but everytime I order something, it takes 3 days to get to my door instead of 2.  I am not upset by that because I would be just as happy with ground shipping, but Prime does offer 2 day shipping and for me it is not 2 day.9.  Memory:  This was a big one for me because the Fire does not have a memory expansion slot.  Before I got my Fire, I looked on my Nook and found out how much memory I had left.  I had a multitude of apps and a lot of books and I used less than 1gb.  I never used the expansion slot for my personal need.  I was still concerned about the Fire with the memory, mainly because of all the reviews out there.  I LOVE the cloud and it suits my needs just fine.  Again, I don't watch a lot of movies or videos on the Fire, so I have plenty of memory for me to use.  I have 1 hour of video, many books and about 50 apps on my Fire and have used less than 1GB.I know there are a lot of consumers out there that are trying to figure out which ereader tablet to buy this holiday season.  Honestly, you can not go wrong with either one.  But in my opinion, I feel the Fire has more features on it than the Nook.4 stars for the Fire.  I will change to 5 if they put on parental controls soon.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment (1)

7 of 7 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsKindle Fire Notes and Observations,November 27, 2011By&nbsp;C. K. G.-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Initial thoughts, the Kindle Fire is much "meatier" than I suspected it would have been. It is a solid piece of hardware and its weight, although not heavy, gives it a very sturdy feel. Time will tell if this is an illusion or a truly robust system. The rubber backing is pleasing to hold and the screen large and crisp. The micro-USB link uses the same chord as the older Kindle (Keyboard) although this is not supplied and must be purchased separately. If, however, you own an older Kindle then you can use that cable to connect the Kindle Fire to the computer. This makes transferring your mp3 files to the music folder possible. Transferring video--at least in the MP4 format--can be done but the files do not play after dragging the files into the video folder until you look at the "Gallery" app. This is the icon that looks like a photo of a mountain scape. Click on that and the videos will appear. Apparently, the cloud does not let you upload your own videos, only those bought by Amazon.  The stereo headphone jack is next to the USB plug, which in turn is next to the on/off button. Since you cannot use the Kindle Fire while it is connected to the computer, space for jacks is not a problem. If you are charging the device this section is tight, but not terribly bothersome. Just to be clear, you can use the Kindle Fire while charging it, although if you are connected to a computer you are locked out until you eject it.There are some reviews that have complained about the placement of the on/off button being inconveniently located; so much so, that the Kindle Fire is often inadvertently turned off. I find this complaint extremely exaggerated because like the Android phones and iPads, once you rotate the device it orients the screen to accommodate the vertical and horizontal. In other words, if the button is on the bottom, after the initial login (if password protected) simply turn the Kindle Fire 180 degrees and the button will be on the top and out the users' way. This seems pretty self evident, but maybe it is just me. I am not concerned with any minor software glitches since I believe most will be corrected with software updates later on. So far, these amount to some lag and some repetition of button pressing during operation. Another example is email which syncs with your account--in my case Hotmail which I used the Hotmail app--but after deleting an email, a subsequent sync will resurrect the deleted emails as if they were new. Again, I think software updates will correct this.I have only downloaded a few apps including Netflix that does not come pre-installed. The movies streamed beautifully and with only a brief and minor loss in resolution, which I suspect is a product of my wireless router trying to keep up and not the Kindle. Angry Birds--the app most people will probably get--worked just fine. Reading, the main reason for owning this device, is similar if not identical to an Android phone with the same options: black, white or sepia backgrounds, text size and font are all available. What is not available is having the text read back to you. Again, just to be clear, Text-to-Speech on the Kindle Fire is not enabled and for me this oversight is a major reason why this review only has four stars instead of five. Also missing are the page numbers which was added on an update to previous Kindle. Hopefully this will be corrected soon. Reading in the full sun is possible with the brightness turned up to 100% although this may limit the battery life. The only concern to outside usage is that buried within the User's Guide (pre-installed) it states that the Kindle Fire has a maximum operating temperature of 95 degrees so having a black device on a hot beach may not be a wise choice.Web surfing is, again, similar to an Android phone and most websites load as if it were a mobile device which is strange considering you must be tethered to a wifi source. It may be due to the screen size which could limit larger webpages readability. This means that most web pages load a "mobile" web page, which can drop videos and photos especially if you are reading your favorite blog. That said, if you go to YouTube you could easily access and watch any video without any hiccups. Pandora is also available and if you really want to open it up you could install the B&N; Nook app to add more books to your collection. This option, however, requires unlocking the device and downloading the B&N; app from another vendor. Just do a Google search for instructions. Having added the Nook app I am apt to rename this the "NooKindle".Overall, it is a solid reader and worth the price tag of $199 although I am not about to discard the e-ink version just yet.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (2)

7 of 7 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsA lot of features and solid performance for an inexpensive tablet,November 23, 2011By&nbsp;BobN2Tech(Orange County, CA USA)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I've had the Kindle Fire for about 1 week now. I am very pleased with its interface, performance, and the content it can access. I bought a 2nd one for my wife as a gift for the upcoming holiday as well.  While I've read critical reviewers that expect the world of features and compare it with the Ipad, they really miss the purpose, value, and quality of this device. The design is simple and uncluttered. Why do we need a designer look? Why do we need a camera, bluetooth, GPS, or mic on a player device? I am carrying an Iphone that does the communications very well and don't need another device for that. Do I really need an HDMI output? If I want to watch on TV, I use my Apple TV or Roku the same content. Or use one of the Apps to stream to the Apple TV.I appreciate the content delivery of music, movies, photos, and the ability to put many "apps" on it for fun and games. I find it to be quite responsive in web browsing, perhaps not as quick as the Ipad or my PC, but it certainly is by no means slow as others may have criticized it.  Movies play back both streaming and on the device in great color with smooth motion. The battery life on streaming seems to be around 5 to 5 1/2 hours, and 6 to 7 hours on movies on the unit with Wifi turned off. This is fine for most situations, even a long flight (how many movies can you watch in a row?). Yes, I would love to have a 24 hour battery so I don't have to charge it, but it's not a deal breaker. The unit is very stable, I have not seen it crash at all. Perhaps, occassionaly it exits the application rarely. This means a lot to me, because that is one of the best virtues the Iphone and Ipad have - stability.Now that all being said, there are 3 items I find somewhat annoying and should be addressed in this model as a firmware update, or the next model:1) No hardware buttons for volume control.What makes this worse, is that the speaker volume and headphone volume are tied together. You can't set the speaker volume independently from the headphone volume. So if you are using the Fire for listening to a movie without a headset, then next time start music or a movie with the headset plugged in, your ears get blasted since normally the speaker volume has to be all the way up to hear it at normal room volume. So Amazon, at least seperate the volume levels! This does not require a hardware change.2) The power button is in a rather awkward spot. It should be on the upper right or left, but not in the center.It's so easy to grab the unit, then rotate it for a movie in the landscape mode and your hand touches the power button momentarily and turns it off.  Now, again Amazon, a simple software fix will take care of this, by requiring the user to hold the power button for 3 seconds to turn it off, and even in that case, a prompt could come up asking if you want to really turn it off.3) A home button would be handy.Again, why not use the power button to get you home by double clicking? That's an easy fix.Although not in the list - because it is not too important, but would be nice - is a light sensor to dim the display at night. It's not a big deal to turn it down, but that would be a nice convenience. As a software feature, maybe something tied to the clock on the unit, so after a preset time, the unit's brightness will lower to some specified percentage.I highly recommend this device for most people that like an easy to use, content rich device. It's reliability is key to not being frustrated with crashes or ill behavior. I would give it five stars if Amazon can address my 3 issues.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp