wser is not. It took about 18 hours to load 425 songs to my Amazon Cloud. Ouch. However, once loaded, I was happy that I now had access to songs on the Kindle Fire that heretofore were only on my home computer. Not only that, but the two small speakers on the KF are actually pretty decent and the headphones I plugged in proved to show that even the headphone output is decent.I ran a few minutes of "Shaun of the Dead," a movie favorite of mine which I bought from Amazon Unbox last year - it looks FABULOUS on the KF. Amazingly clear picture.I uploaded a few photos of my family into the Gallery app and they are crystal clear when zooming through. Love that I can now see my kids' faces whenever the urge strikes.I haven't tried the lending function yet since I only got it yesterday, but I'm looking forward to using that.Basically, the conclusion I've come to is that if you want a tablet strictly for basic entertainment (books, movies, music, basic email, basic web surfing), then the Kindle Fire is perfect for you. If you want a tablet for entertainment AND the ability to videochat, create a Powerpoint presentation, and use GPS to keep from getting lost while out driving - well, then another tablet would be a better bet. But for those who don't need all that, but just want easy access to their own media content with a couple perks on top, then this is the way to go.But the day the Kindle Fire comes out with 3G? That IS an upgrade I'll sign up for even if I'm satisfied with my current Kindle Fire!!Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

