7 of 7 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsExceptional value, but with limitations....,November 15, 2011By&nbsp;D. Porter(UT USA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)THE VERDICTI've been playing with the new Kindle Fire for about 8 hours now, and overall I am impressed with it.  It is a good item at a fantastic price.  A few conclusions:- This is a good choice for 60% of the tablet users out there.  Once set up, it is just as easy to use as anything else (IPad included).  While there are a few items that true power users will miss (camera, etc.) most people will find this device does most everything they will ask it to do.- There is a bit more skill required to set this up than an IPad, certainly having either Android experience or a technical friend will help.- Absolutely necessary if you have been purchasing Kindle books, using Amazon Cloud to manage your music and other content, and are an Amazon Prime member.- At this price point, I can't think of anything that can compete in with the hardware.  I feel like I stole it.I bought this as a gift for a non-technical user.  After seeing how easy it is to use, I'll be buying more.  Honestly, my retired parents (who can barely use the remote control to their cable TV) could use this tablet.  So could my grandmother.  Un-freaking-believable for $200 bucks.  Just be ready to embrace the Amazon.com content world.THE DETAILSI work in technology, and have used many similar devices including ITouch, IPad, Android phones (several, current is an EVO 4G), and both Motorola and Samsung Android tablets.  I bought this for my wife's birthday (for her, not me ;) ).  She uses email, web, etc. on our home PC but has never really tried mobile devices.  Having set this up and played with it, I am very satisfied with my purchase.  I am also confident that my wife will easily be able to use the Kindle Fire immediately.While the interface lacks the traditional Android buttons, it took no time for me to figure out.  Amazon has done an excellent job at layout of functions, and overall the interface is simple to drive.  Setting up wireless took seconds.  I was then able to log into my Amazon Prime account, and quickly download both kindle books and audio I had stored on the Amazon Cloud.  Installation of about 10 apps took a few more minutes.  I like the interface to the Amazon App Store better than the default Google marketplace apps on my other Android devices.  With this as a starting point, I began playing with the device.The form factor is elegant.  I particularly like the rubbery-feeling grippy material on the back.  The display is beautiful, and the resolution is crisp even at an angle.  I could have three kids watch a movie on this no problem.  While it is a little heavy to hold one-handed for an extended period of time, it certainly feels better in the hand than an 10".  Due largely to the high screen resolution, I didn't feel like I was missing much real estate from the 10".The web browser is responsive and easy to use.  I added a few bookmarks in minutes.  Amazon claims that they do some pre-processing of web sites in the cloud to optimize your web experience.  Whatever they are doing is seamless, I was able to browse multiple types of content without issue.  I spent some time on YouTube, looking at Flash-enabled content, and reading news.  All worked fine.I installed Angry Birds, Plants vs. Zombies, Cut the Rope, NetFlix, Doodle Jump, and several productivity apps.  All tested and worked fine.  I've had problems with NetFlix on my phones, so I spent 30 minutes or so playing with that app.  No problems, which surprised me a bit.++ATTN New Users - One note on the email client - I spent about 30 minutes searching for the default email app, and then reading online to find out what I was doing wrong.  About 2 hours after I started up the Kindle Fire, it downloaded an update that placed the email app in the application repository.  I had already checked to see that my Kindle was up to date, it said it was.  Obviously Amazon had pushed down an update with the email app (and who knows what else).  So, if you just fired up your new Kindle Fire and can't find the email app, give it an hour or two to wait for that initial update push.The email client, once set up, works great at managing my wife's multiple email accounts.I did get a little frustrated when I could not find several favorite Android apps in the Amazon App Store.  However, I quickly found the setting to allow 3rd party apps to be installed (under settings in the device menu there is a switch to allow apps from unknown sources).  I was then able to install a 3rd party app, but struck out on 3-4 others (errors about the app not being in the Amazon store).  A little frustrating, and something I'll need to work on in the next few days.The only other thing I felt was lacking was a social networking app.  Honestly, I'm a little surprised there is no pre-installed app for Facebook and Twitter.  I poked around the Amazon App Store, but have not yet selected an app for social networking.  The web browser is just not the correct interface for social, and I'm a little surprised there wasn't a pre-installed app for this.Overall I'm happy with the device hardware and interface.  As a long-time Amazon.com user and first-time Kindle owner, the experience of accessing my Amazon content was superb.  I'm a little worried about getting apps from outside the Amazon App Store installed, more that it is going to be harder than it should be than I won't be able to do it.++UPDATED 11/16I spent several more hours trying to install third party apps not available in the Amazon App Store, with no luck.  I tried several app stores (GetJar, etc.) and while some things do work, the 6 or so particular apps that my wife wants are not available anywhere.  While I appreciate that Amazon may want to insure that apps will function on the device (don't install an app that needs a camera for instance), I wish I could truly take of the safety net and install apps on my own.  A little big-brother feeling to me, and part of the reason I left Apple.  It's not like I'm trying to install a Barnes and Noble Nook reader or anything, although some have.To anyone with previous Android experience, I'd recommend pre-screening your apps on Amazon.com before purchasing a Kindle Fire.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

