7 of 7 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsOutstanding content device for Amazon,November 15, 2011By&nbsp;B. Anderson(Queen Creek, AZ USA)  -See all my reviews(VINE VOICE)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I'm a pretty big gadget junkie, and I love (pretty much) all things Amazon, so when the Fire was announced, I knew I had to have one.  I've owned Android devices over the past year, so I have a good idea as to what to expect from the operating system.I'm not going to go into huge detail about all the pros and cons of the device; this has been done in exhaustive detail in other reviews, and I don't want to bore you by regurgitating the same details.  However, there are a few things I noticed pretty quickly about the device:+++ It's pretty responsive.  I've used other Android devices, and they all seem to suffer from stuttering of the display when you swipe or press on something. The Fire does a good job of allowing for a smoother experience.+++ Amazon has essentially gutted the Android interface and replaced it with their own, so the Fire will decidedly not be your mom's Android device. When you start up your Fire, it will walk you through the interface, which is a nice touch. It's pretty easy to navigate, with all the categories of the things you can do at the top of the screen.  They've also replaced the standard Android web browser with their own, which - I hate to say it - works a little better than the native Android browser.--- You can *not* go to the Android Marketplace at all. I tried going to the Marketplace through Google and every other way, and it always neatly redirects me to the Amazon App Store. People concerned with their devices being completely open will probably freak about this, and I don't know of a jailbreak for the Fire just yet (give it a week or so, I'm sure).  Personally, I don't mind this - the apps through Amazon tend to be kind of "vetted", meaning there are fewer junk apps on Amazon. However, this is why I rated the Fire 4 stars instead of 5.Overall, if you're looking for an excellent and intuitive content device for Amazon that you can also play games, surf the web, and send email from, this is for you.  If you're interested in hacking your Android device or installing Android Marketplace-specific apps, you should definitely look elsewhere.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

