9 of 10 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsExcellent EReader With Benefits,November 29, 2011By&nbsp;Amy C(Kansas City, MO USA)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)BACKGROUND:I/we do not own ANY Apple products, tablets, or previous e-readers.  Consider myself fairly tech savvy as I own 2 desktops (one for gaming, the other custom built for myself), a Dell laptop, an HP netbook, and we are heavy HTC/Android users in the family.OK, so let me just say that reading some of these reviews almost made me NOT buy the Fire because no one compared it apples to apples.  First of all, it is NOT a tablet or iPad; it's an e-Reader with benefits.WHY I BOUGHT IT:My daughter loves to read. She loves to listen to music.  She absolutely loves TV shows and movies.  She plays games on her phone.  She gets on the internet almost daily.  She carries around a VERY heavy laptop when traveling.WHAT FIRE PROVIDES FOR MY DAUGHTER'S NEEDS:Books! Music! Movies! TV Shows! Games! Internet! Lightweight in comparison to a laptop!In playing with the Fire for the past week, I have fallen in love with it.  So much that my family jokes about me not giving it to my daughter for Christmas.WHERE FIRE EXCEEDS MY EXPECTATIONS:- The EASE of set up.  I basically opened the box, turned it on, logged into my wireless network and BAM - I was off and running.- The screen.  I feel like I'm watching HDTV on a 7 inch screen!  Incredibly crisp and full of color. Definitely works as a replacement to a portable DVD player when taking long trips (under 8 hours).- The battery life. I played two movies back to back, read 8% of a book while listening to music, and played on Facebook &amp; Words with Friends for about an hour before the battery icon started to look helpless.- The sound.  While not extremely loud, it still is fairly loud in a quiet situation like airplane travel, or library or coffee shops.  I would suggest headphones.- The use of Amazon Prime. Now I get a discount because I'm a student so I did not pay $79.  BUT I love Prime and the benefits; so having a Kindle now only makes my Prime account more beneficial! Plus if you break it down it's like $6 a month...WHERE FIRE DISAPPOINTS:- I have not taken the Fire outside of the house, because the games I like to play need an active wireless connection.  So depending on the games you download; this "could" be a problem.  That and it's a gift, HA!  Along the same lines, the TV Shows only "stream" so if you don't have a connection, this part is really worthless while traveling.- Weight. Double edged sword.  While lightweight in comparison to a laptop or netbook - this little sucker is heavy enough to make it feel uncomfortable holding in your hands. I always feel like I'm going to drop it after a while.  So I normally set it on the table while using it.  I would suggest a cover that props up the unit.SILLY LITTLE THINGS THAT SHOULDN'T MATTER:- When you buy it from Amazon, and log in with your Amazon account - it picks up YOU as the primary user and also loads your shopping preferences.  The are two ways to get around it, one is to DEREGISTER it, have the person using it sign up for an Amazon account and register it there. Or two, you can go in and change the name in the "manage kindle" section of Amazon. I was able to change her name &amp; email - but it still said registered to me. Both of these do NOT work for me. One, I don't want to pay for TWO prime memberships and two, she has access to my preferences using my account; and not hers.  Vice versa when I search for preferences I have hers now included.  This should be an easy fix on Amazon's side - get your programmers on it!- The forcing of 1-click set up even to download FREE items.  This is annoying. I went ahead and set up the Kindle one-click with a bogus credit card, so it doesn't allow unauthorized purchases.  But once my daughter gets it she can load her own credit card into those separate settings. She's 17 and has a job - thank goodness!- The price of accessories &amp; warranty.  My daughter is prone to dropping items. Getting the warranty, cover &amp; headphones - is another $100 worth of items!  That's a grand total of $300.  Something I really neglected to think about before buying her this. Although, I will buy it (grumble).- The bookshelf/memory/carousel screen. The main screen saves your favorites and then shows you your past history, even of websites.  Not really an issue as I don't view questionable material, but it is kind of annoying and really not necessary.  I'd rather have a full screen of favorites instead. Also even if you clear your browser history, when you open your browser again the old sites sometimes still show up.  I am not sure if this is a glitch or I'm doing something wrong - but annoying to say the least.OVERALL - FINAL ADVICE:If you care more about books than other media - don't buy it!  Buy a regular Kindle and enjoy the long battery life.If you want a fully functional, internet driven, media powerhouse - consider a tablet.  I just saw that the HTC EVO View tablet is on sale for $249, pretty close in price but remember you'll pay a hefty monthly fee for that constant connection and you'll need accessories too!For me, I love it. A few annoyances, but nothing that will force me to send it back. I can't wait for my daughter to open it on Christmas (reset to factory default of course) .. I hope she loves it as much as I do!!Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

