rary- I would suggest we all send in request - and Amazon will take it into serious considerationAs for the the rest of this mini review - initial impressions is that it is much better build quality, and has a solid feel.Screens move adequately - and overall ease of use is nice -  I agree with other reviews - a volume up/down and home button would be a plus....but aren't deal killers for me.The real value will be the Amazon Prime content - streaming TV - Movies - and the lending library - combine that with the thousands of free and low priced Kindle books and this appears to be a great early unitThe reading experience - though not as easy on the eyes as E-Ink- is easily modified with a change of background - and doesn't require a case with a separate reading light.  The light with the original Kindle is great - but adds a premium - when you factor in a back light on this unit - it is like saving $50-$60I like the soft tactical feel of the back - and the screen does not appear to need a Zagg Skin - for extra protection - another $$ saverI have not fully tested the unit - but hope some of the hysterics about 1 click and all can be put in proper prospectiveHope this helpsHelp other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

9 of 10 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsNot gonna lie....it's pretty awesome,November 17, 2011By&nbsp;Cole Everman "Coleman"(Seattle, WA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I've been on my Kindle Fire non-stop for 2 days now. I've put it through its paces and think I've done enough on it to write a well-informed review.First, I'm amazed at how fun and easy the device is. It's very intuitive. I have an iPad and have spent a lot of time on a friends Motorola tablet...and I like the Fire better than both. It fits in your hand, it feels very nice to hold, it's easy to use, it's fast, and it gets me to the things that matter (email, web, Facebook, kindle books collection, Amazon Prime movies/content, Hulu+, Netflix, Pandora and Magazines) much faster and easier than the endless sea of apps that are on other tablets. The Silk web browser (for the most part) has been extremely fast. Web pages render faster than they do with my iPad in a side by side comparison. I'm really happy that Amazon allowed the Hulu+ and Netflix apps as well. I think that was an extremely classy move on Amazon's part. Amazon could have forced all Fire owners to use the Amazon ecosystem and buy all their content. However, they allowed two other content competitors onto their own device. Now I have access to a TON of content that streams pretty seamlessly. I'm impressed.Now, there have been a few hiccups. In the two days of use I managed to freeze the device once...but I also had Pandora playing and 10 or 11 web pages open. I held the power button down for 20 seconds and restarted the device and it's been all rosy from there. There have also been a few times when the web browser was a little slow and unresponsive. However, it remedied itself. I think part of this was the device and part was my internet connection...which can be horribly spotty sometimes.PROS: Feels great, great size, totally portable, great ecosystem, easy to use, Hulu+ and Netflix support, fast browser, good email client, great screen, funCONS: Limited storage on the device (I'm a fan of the cloud but it could use a few gigs more), no way to password protect or create folders to keep people from accessing your content (I don't want to hand the device over to my friends kids for Angry Birds with my R-rated movies on there)Overall, the thing that impresses me most about this device is that it's fun. It's hard to not pick it up and play with it. Yes, there are a few issues, but honestly I don't think there are any that can't be fixed with a software update from Amazon (which I'm sure they're working on). Good job Amazon.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (3)

9 of 10 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsSolid, interesting, dependable, versatile,November 17, 2011By&nbsp;J. Paul(Huntington Beach, CA United States)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)See updated review below.*******************Received my Fire yesterday. Immediately tapped into my 'stuff'. Yes! I instantly logged into Wifi at my office and a few hours later at home. No problema.I purchased the Fire to test the tablet waters. I have been looking at iPad, Samsung, etc for months and wanted to put an end to this part of my little life so that I can get on to the next whatever that my desires point at...Anyway, the price point was perfect, the gift card opportune, etc.; and I know that I can return it in the next 30 days if ultimately unsatisfied.The tablet is my answer to getting past walking my laptop and wires from one room to another every night to use it in front of the tv. It looks like this tablet is fine for that application.One thing that I ended up wanting was a device that works simply and quickly right out of the box; I have long since passed the part of my life that is interested in spending a lot of upfront time figuring how a device works, configuring it, adding content spread out all over etc. The ability of the Fire to come to me already set up was a significant benefit. I will eventually, at my leisure, poke around the Fire and learn from others in the discussion forums about the little shortcuts, etc.In thinking about tablets, I thought alot about size. The 7 inch form is small but I have adjusted to this within a couple of hours of use. I watched a couple of free Arrested Development TV programs and was instantly enjoying the experience. Downloaded a weather app, and then I went to a couple of websites I often visit and read them. Yes, I had to scroll some, but this is my trade off for a smaller more portable form factor. I also read some books and listened to my music. The back-lighted reading experience is not so objectionable (I do have a wonderful keyboard Kindle to compare). I used the white text on black background, reduced the brightness and it was no problem. Yes the Kindle keyboard is unsurpassed in readability, but the Fire is very nice as well.Now, back to the 7 inch form... The other side of that size equation was the much bigger size of the iPad and other android tablets that I had shopped. I always felt that it was like I was carrying around a sizable device and it just did not fit how I saw using such a device. I have my laptop if I want a laptop.So, my first impressions are very positive. It is what I expected and more. I am not looking for a perfect experience; everything has its trade-offs and the trade-offs here are - so far - well within tolerance.My rating is not about the perfectness or some comparison to another device... it is about how it stacks up against my original, well researched expectations.*************************Update 11/26/11So I am now a couple of weeks into the Fire. For reading I am picking up my Kindle Keyboard... not the Fire.The video experience is good; vivid and works at about a B+ level. Apps are interesting but I am not really using them; the email reader is fine (Hotmail and Gmail).Web experience - I look at a couple of web sites and dont really like the scrolling around to read. The text is too small for me. I know this is 7 inches but now that I am doing all the scrolling, I am thinking that a larger form factor is more to my taste.Playing music is fine, the speakers are adequate but a touch tinny to the ear.As mentioned in my first review, I wanted to use the tablet in place of the laptop in front of the TV, but I need a better web experience than what the Fire affords me.I like to buy things that really add to my life. The Kindle Keyboard did that, the laptop does that, the TV does that. The Fire is pretty much another device that I have to kind of squeeze in because I think I should... not because it has earned a  niche in my life.I like the concept of a thin, light, portable, easy to hold, simple, video and web player device that is easy to read on that I can replace the laptop with but I am starting to think that maybe a tablet device is just not additive enough to deserve my money and attention.I will revisit the ipad and samsung 10 devices, maybe...******************************Well, my wife said that this was a birthday gift so I decided to keep it. So I am looking at it differently.I still really like the Kindle Keyboard (KKB) for reading. The Fire is a little bright but doable. If I had just the Fire, I would use it fine for reading. Reading outside is inferior to the KKB. The fact that it does so many things makes it more generally an entertainment device vs. the KKB. I enjoy the music playing. The video playing is fine as a personal device. Sometimes I watch a video while doing something on my laptop. I use the web in a fairly circumscribed way because of the small viewer. It is something to play with in front of the TV - but I have to admit, the laptop is better (damn the wires; only 100 or so minute battery). Anyway, as I play with it I learn more about it.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

