6 of 6 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsKindle Fire Experience after 3 months Ownership,February 15, 2012By&nbsp;Chidi Sr.(KS, USA)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I have had a few Kindle Fire devices over the past 3 months. I purchased the first one in late November 2011. After playing with it a bit, I was quite intrigued by the approach and concept taken by Amazon. The price being extraordinarily great and the user experience very smooth, I bought a few more.I really didn't want the Kindle Fire for myself - I am a techie. I believe the absence of the full Android market and some Google applications, kept me out. But for those who can live without those Google services, and Swype-like keyboards, this is a steal. You would not miss the cameras or Bluetooth since most smart phones have those and for many, those are non-essential on a tablet.On the Fire you can play games, do online homework on the school web sites, visit flash-based game sites, and watch Netflix, Youtube and Prime video on demand. There are lots of books, games and applications in the Amazon Android and Kindle store. The Kindle Fire experience is a kids dream.If you hook the Fire up to a computer via USB it appears as a convenient hard drive. No software needed. You just drag and drop what you need to take on the road. There isn't a lot of space but there is enough space to store 3 or 4 full length (8+ hours) compressed movies for the road. For your locally stored home videos or music on Fire, you will need an application like "Avia Media Player" to play them.The user interface is smooth, first graders will master the interface in minutes. Some things need getting used to but can be picked up quickly. Nothing is really out of place or non intuitive. It could be a bit more responsive at times but that is just a quibble. The power button is  fine, the USB charging is quick and simple. You will need a wired headset if you want great sound, but who doesn't have one of those these days.I recently lost one of my Fires. The battery wouldn't charge. No problem with the others though. I contacted Amazon and they shipped a replacement via two day shipping immediately. Amazon customer service for Kindle Fire was great - less than 1 minute wait time, easy to use chat sessions and quick call back, plus prepaid shipping (both ways).For an affordable 7 inch tablet with full web compatibility (including flash) that is almost a complete replacement for any kiddos net-book or desktop (for online lessons, games and homework), it is a super deal. If you need a gift for a non-techie friend or family, get them one of these. You will not regret it!Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

