6 of 6 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsGetting just what you paid for, and then more!,November 17, 2011By&nbsp;Cassandra M. Hammond(San Diego, CA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)First of all - I love my Kindle Fire! I had a Kindle Keyboard prior to this, but wanted to upgrade when I heard about the upcoming Fire. Here I will go over the features by category.E-Reading:As an e-reader, the Kindle Fire is just as good as it's predecessors. Naturally the big difference is between the e-ink technology and the LCD backlit screen. Having used both, I will admit I prefer the e-ink technology used in the other Kindle models. However, the LCD screen isn't too big of an issue for me. When I want to read at night I simply change the screen to black with white text, and I find that it makes it much easier for me to read without worrying about my eyes hurting too quickly (I was able to do a good two hours before getting tired, and typically that was how long I would read on my Kindle Keyboard while using a booklight). The page turns are just as quick, if not faster. Also, I love getting color covers for my books!Apps:One big draw for me was the tablet-like functions that the Kindle Fire has. immediately I picked up some favorite apps through the Amazon App Store. For me, this was no big deal. I own a Droid phone, and use the Amazon app store regularly because of their free app per day. To test it out I played Plants vs Zombies, and it looked amazing! It was much better than playing on my phone, and I had no issues with flow of the game.Browsing:I bought this understanding that for the price this is not going to be an iPad (which is why I don't understand why Apple fans are QQing, there is a great number of people who are buying the Fire because they cannot afford the iPad). Regardless, I found that the browser was faster than my expectations! For the price I was expecting something that would move at a decent speed, but was surprised to find that it flowed nicely and that I was able to go on Tumblr (a site that gives high latency because of it's many graphics) without experiencing much lag at all.Documents:I love it! Not only is it nicely organized, but all documents uploaded flow just like books when reading them. It is a very good feature, especially for a college student like me!Video &amp; Music:With the free month of Prime that comes with the purchase of the Kindle Fire I chose to test out how nice movies looked. I was very pleased, and found it much better than trying to watch a movie on my iTouch. The audio was good quality, and with the beautiful color display the Kindle Fire is definitely great for media.All in all, I think that this is a wonderful product for the price you pay. As a college student I hate lugging around a laptop, but I also cannot afford an iPad or any of the other higher-end tablets. The Kindle Fire really gives you the essentials, and with that in mind $199 is an amazing price. One warning though for anyone who did not take note of contents, there is no usb cord! With the Kindle Keyboard the charger was a usb cord that plugged into the adapter, but this is not the case with the Kindle Fire.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

