11 of 13 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsGreat Product!!,December 17, 2011By&nbsp;Grateful Mom(South Plainfield, NJ USA)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I'd like to say that I am a 12-year old boy and my father has the iPad 2. This is NOT an iPad killer so don't expect this to beat Apple's iPad in specs.IN THE BOX: In the box is the Kindle, a charger, and a getting to know your Kindle sheet. Once you set up your Wi-Fi connection, and time zone, you can start using the Kindle. It comes pre-registered with all your content, so I found all my books from my Kindle app on it. There is a Kindle Fire User's Guide and A Dictionary built into the Kindle.Exterior: On the bottom is the power button, headphone jack, and connection port. There is a soft back covering that feels nice in your hand, and the front is supported with Gorilla Glass.DELETING ITEMS: People have said that you can't delete items and it's in your cloud forever. That's not true. If they went online to their account and clicked Managing Your Kindle, they would see all their content and notice that there are available actions to do with your content, one of them deleting your content forever.HOME SCREEN: You cannot move around your recently viewed items carousel, but you can add them to your favorites section. It also shows tabs: Search, Newsstand, Books, Music, Video, Docs, Apps, and Web.RESPONIVENESS: People have been saying that the responsiveness is iffy and you have to keep tapping. Sometimes it can be too responsive, and sometimes not, but if you can be patient with the Kindle, it will work. If you tap too much, obviously it's not going to work.OPTIONS: When you're in the home screen or anywhere, you can tap on the cog in the top right, and it will show you basic options: Volume, Brightness, Wi-Fi, Sync Unlocked/Locked, which helps you to lock your Kindle in a portrait or landscape position. There is also MORE, where you can check your account, sounds, display, SECURITY, where you can add a passcode to block your Kindle from others, Applications, Date and Time, Kindle Keyboard, and Device.NOTIFICATIONS: If you tap the top left next to your name, it will pop up notifications from your apps and the device. You cannot open notifications unless you have a notification.PRE-INSTALLED APPS: Your Kindle will come with pre-installed apps that you CAN delete if you go to Manage Your Kindle. These apps are Audible, Comics, Contacts, Mail, ESPN Score Center, Facebook, Gallery, Help &amp; Feedback, IMDB, Pandora, Pulse, Quickoffice, Amazon Shopping App, and The Weather Channel.MAGAZINES AND BOOKS: Amazon has a wide selection of Books and Magazines, and you can sample a magazine for 14 days and can get a free sample of a book for as long as you want. When you tap on an item, it will give you some brief information about the book or magazine.APPS: Amazon also has over 14,000 apps, and one of those paid apps is free every day, very convenient.Most of these apps are popular, so it's not just 14,000 pointless apps. There ks obviously Angry Birds Rio, Seasons, and Regular. They also have Angry Birds HD for $4.99. There is also Scrabble, Doodle Jump, and Plants vs. Zombies. So you can see the app store is really nicely put together. On the home for the apps screen, it shows the normally paid free app, and the top 100 free and top 100 paid apps. Again, I like the app store layout.VIDEO: You can rent or buy videos, and some are free for Prime Members. EX. You can rent Harry Potter for $5.99 for 48 hours in HD. You can also see a video summary of whatever movie or TV show you would like to see.MUSIC: There is a nice selection of Music, and Amazon offers daily deals for this music. They give you a 30 second preview of the song you select. The price range for music starts from $0.69 to $1.29, so not bad pricing, especially cheaper than the iPad.BATTERY: The battery is not the best I've seen, but is pretty good unless you plan on being on it all day.READING: The reading experience is nice, with different typefaces available and margin spacing and different sizes and of course text lighting.WEB: The web is nice, with available tabs and bookmark options. It is not as fast as it claims, but is nice. Amazon's own website takes about 6 seconds to load.OVERALL: I definitely recommend this to anyone who wants all the content, an easy UI to handle, and portability. Buy the iPad if you want all the apps, fast web, and a great, easy experience. That's all, I'm going to go enjoy my new Kindle now!!!!!Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment (1)

