8 of 9 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsAmazing tablet!,December 19, 2011By&nbsp;maestag-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)This little tablet is quite spectacular.Here's a quick review:Device:While the device doesn't offer too many options for personalizing, I've found that the interface is pleasing, convenient, and easy to use. I would like the device itself to have volume control, rather than having to adjust it on the screen. It seems to be the perfect size for me. It's smaller than the iPad at 7 in. and 14.6 oz. The screen seems pretty tough and is clear at any angle. The battery will last all day. There is no option for additional storage other than the cloud on top of its built in 8gb (about 6.5gb available for use). I like the home bar that allows you to go home, go back, view the menu, or perform a search within the content libraries or the web. The carousel is fun to use in order to view your most recent activity. The only button is the power button.Newsstand:There are many magazine and newspaper subscriptions available. The store has an easy to use interface. The only problem is that magazines can take up quite a bit of memory for a device that just has 8gb available. This can be remedied from Amazon's cloud (which comes with 5gb for free). You can view your magazine in page view or text view.Books:Like the Newsstand, the book store is easy to use. Books download in seconds. There are a bunch of free books to download (a lot of classics) and even more if you're an Amazon Prime member (you get one month for free). You don't have to worry about space, as these books take up a negligible amount of memory on the device (plus you can always use the cloud). When you're reading your book, you can change the font style, line spacing, margins, color mode (The black background and white text is good for night reading-the light tan background and brown text is easy on the eyes-and the white background and black text is what you'd find on any LCD e reader). You can also change the font style to your preference. The built in dictionary makes it easy to look up definitions while you're reading. The search feature is also nice for looking up phrases or passages within the book. The kindle remembers where you're at when you leave the book, though you can also add bookmarks within the book. I suppose that the only disadvantage would be the LCD screen, as it can mess with your eyes after reading on it for too long. However, it is nice for reading in the dark. You can adjust the screen brightness.Music:I was pleasantly surprised with the music aspect of the kindle fire. For a tablet, it has pretty decent little speakers (you can also use headphones). You don't have to worry about not being able to use iTunes on the device. Amazon's mp3 uploader allows you to upload all of your music (from iTunes as well) (mp3 and m4a) to the kindle's music library. Your music will be downloaded in the cloud (5gb available for free, if you want more than that you can upgrade to 20gb (or more-up to 1000) and unlimited music storage for a dollar for every gb-per year). You can then download your uploaded music to the device (say if you know you won't have internet access) to your device (keep in mind, the device itself only has 8gb of memory). The interface is pleasant and user friendly. You can organize your music library by artist, album, or song. You can create playlists. Multitasking is easy, as you can play your music while reading, surfing the web, or playing with your apps. I would prefer that the device had volume control on the device itself rather than having to use the screen to do so, but it's really not that much of a hassle. Like the Newsstand and Books, you have access to amazon's Music store as well.Video:If you want, you can store your own digital copies of movies onto the device. Though, I think the primary use for video is access to Amazon's video store, which has a wide selection of movies and TV shows. You can rent new releases for $2.99. If you are an Amazon Prime member, thousands of free videos are available for instant streaming. You get one month of Amazon Prime membership for free.Docs:This was another feature that I was surprised with. This feature allows you to email yourself documents (DOC, DOCX, PDF, HTML, TXT, RTF, JPEG, GIF, PNG, BMP, PRC, and MOBI) to be stored onto your device.Apps:There are thousands of apps available for download. There are plenty of free apps, and (I found this quite nice) one free app of the day! The market isn't quite as large as that of apple, but there are plenty of apps to keep you entertained. Much of the top apps like Angry Birds, Netflix, Pulse, SimCity, Quickoffice, Pandora, and Evernote are available. The kindle fire comes with a few useful apps already downloaded onto the device (like Quickoffice, Pandora, IMDb, Contacts, Gallery, and Email). The email app is pretty neat. You can check each of your email accounts in one unified inbox (or separately if you prefer). I also like the Comics app. There are plenty of comics available for free and even more for purchase. The kindle fire makes viewing comics (as well as graphic novels) a wonderful experience. There are two ways to organize your apps, by recent and by title. I would prefer a bit more flexibility with organizing the apps. You can copy your favorite apps onto the homepage as well. Any app that you download will be saved on the cloud even if you delete it from your device.Web:Amazon Silk is quick and easy. It supports bookmarks, history, and searches. Your most visited pages appear as thumbnails on new tabs.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment (1)

