8 of 9 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsAn Affordable Toy,December 2, 2011By&nbsp;William A. Adams(Tucson, AZ USA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Kindle Fire is a fun toy for a low-risk price so I tried it. I like it, but I don't need it. For reading books, the regular Kindle is far superior, due to the E-ink display which is just like reading on paper. I have two of those. Kindle Fire is attractive for accessing the internet when I am away from my desk. I use my home Wi-fi so I can browse email while watching TV on the couch, can look up the cable program guide while I watch, consult IMDB and other movie reviews, look up words, translate foreign phrases, check facts, make quick notes to myself, read the NY Times book review, etc. I can get recipes in the kitchen, share photos in the dining room, listen to .mp3 songs in bed. It's a toy. You can't make phone calls on it, you can't do any serious work with it, and you don't really need it.Could I use my 5 lb HP laptop to do everything the K-fire does?  Yes, but the laptop is heavy, large, awkward to hold, gets too hot and takes 15 minutes (it seems) to start. So I use the Kindle because it's convenient and I'm lazy. Kindle Fire has some nice apps, like Audible (audio books) and Pandora (radio). They're also available on my PC, but the Kindle is far more practical when traveling, car or plane, or moving around the house. (It is no longer practical to use a PC on a plane because the seating space is so tight. If the guy in front of you reclines, you are out of luck.)The K-Fire Silk Browser is perfectly acceptable. The amazon cloud storage is basically unlimited, so that eliminates a standard problem with portable devices (as long as you are connected to the cloud). Another plus is that it is not Apple, which means your music is .mp3 and belongs to you, not them. Likewise, the software is Android, which means Apple does not control your content. Wifi-only connection means no bloodsucking contract for monthly data fees. Battery life is quite acceptable, depending on what you're doing, the better part of a day of use, but see note below.The down side: Huge negative: I put it away without turning off the Wi-Fi and the battery completely discharged and could not be revived. Have to send it in for a replacement unit and reload all my apps. A hassle but not a show-stopper, though I recommend purchasing the 2 year extended warranty. Other points: The touch screen is not as sensitive as I would like. Taps often don't work at first and there is no feedback, so I feel like a woodpecker. With all controls on-screen, the device essentially cannot be controlled without looking. That means it is virtually unusable while driving and not very useful for listening in bed. Even in landscape mode, the screen is slightly too small to make the on-screen keyboard usable for a touch typist, so the device is not practical as a note-taker, a big disappointment for me. Since it is Wi-Fi only, you can't use it while you are on the go to research products, restaurants, directions, etc. There is no GPS app (and it wouldn't do any good anyway, since you would  need a traveling Wifi connection). Some web sites are "non-PC-standard" when accessed by the Silk browser. Google, for example shows no Maps or Videos on its menus and you have to poke around quite deeply to find and access those features. I had some trouble installing Gmail but eventually managed it by ignoring the Kindle Email app and going directly through Google via the browser. Reading newspapers and magazines is a bit of a strain since the type is so small. You can zoom in, but then you have no context of where you are on the page. It can be done, but it's not great. Google News is usable. NYTimes just barely. I haven't figured out how to install NYTimes' "Times Reader" on the K-fire. Once I figure that out, I should be fine. When you use the Kindle to download a movie, it streams live over the wifi connection as you watch, which is not as reliable, fast, or convenient as a straight download to storage. I download Amazon movies to my PC or Tivo then play them from disk, which is far more flexible and smooth than trying to use the Kindle Fire. Wi-fi is a plus for being economical, but a negative if you want to be truly portable, and that means social networking is limited to when you are at a hotspot. There simply are not as many useful apps for Android as there are for Apple, but that should change over time. However, there are extremely few useful business or productivity apps for the K-Fire, so it is no threat to the laptop in that regard. K-Fire is not a work tool. You can't even really use it to take meeting notes, and if you did, it is not clear what you would do then. Email the notes to your desk PC? One trivial but extremely annoying K-Fire trait is that you cannot uninstall or delete the apps that come preloaded with the device. Most of them are useless to me and simply clutter up the interface.  There are some apps that do "app-removing" but none of them I have tried can remove the pre-installed bloatware.Conclusion: I like the Kindle Fire and my wife and I use it at home anytime we are away from desk and PC on the couch, on the patio, in the kitchen, or at the airport. We use regular E-ink Kindles for reading while traveling. I have zero interest in online games so that eliminates a large category of tablet functionality for me. I would have to say that 90% of the apps available are of little or no value to me. I can use the browser to get all the news, weather and sports I need. So the Kindle Fire is basically a fun toy at an affordable price and for that, it is well worth it.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

