8 of 9 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsExcellent for Its Intended Purpose,November 18, 2011By&nbsp;J. Cheshire-See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I'll begin by saying that the Kindle Fire is not an iPad, and Amazon didn't intend it to be. Instead, it's a device aimed squarely at consuming Amazon content. If you enjoy Amazon's MP3 Store, Amazon Instant Video, the Kindle Store, and the benefits of Amazon Cloud Drive, you will love the Kindle Fire.MUSIC:I pay $20 per year for 20GB of storage on my Amazon Cloud Drive. That plan also provides me with unlimited storage for my music files, whether purchased from Amazon or not. I love being able to stream my music from any Web browser, but I don't always have a computer with me.The Kindle Fire's Music library directly integrates with my music that's on my Amazon Cloud Drive. As long as I have an Internet connection, I can stream any of my music, and unlike doing it from a Web browser, the experience is first class. If I want to carry some of my music with me, I can download it to the Kindle Fire and listen when I'm not online. (The Kindle Fire has about 6.5GB of user-available memory.)VIDEO:I discovered Amazon Instant Video about a year ago. It's a great service with high-quality video, much of which is in HD and with 5.1 surround. Using the Kindle Fire, I have instant access to videos in my library, but I can also easily rent or purchase videos right from the device. As a Prime member, I can watch thousands of titles at no additional charge. (Prime selection isn't that great, but new titles are being added frequently.)Because the Kindle Fire's display ratio is widescreen, 16:9 video fills the display. In a side-by-side comparison with the iPad's larger display, actual size of video being played on the Kindle Fire is almost identical. In other words, the 7" screen on the Kindle Fire isn't a handicap when watching video.Incidentally, Netflix, Hulu Plus, and your own videos can also be watched on the Kindle Fire.MAGAZINES, NEWSPAPERS, BOOKS, and MOREReading on the Kindle Fire is as expected on an LCD device; it's not quite as comfortable as reading E Ink. However, because the Kindle Fire's display is about the size of a paperback page, it's much easier to read on it than a large LCD screen.Magazines and newspapers are great on the Kindle Fire, and not only because they are in color. The navigation of periodicals is great, and the new Page View feature incorporated into many magazines maintains the appearance of the print copy.The Kindle Fire also offers a wide array of children's books that look great and offer unique features. Graphic novels and comic books are also available, but many of the DC comics aren't available for a few more days.APPSAmazon's Android app store contains a wide array of applications, all of which will work well on the Kindle Fire. Amazon offers a paid app free every day, and these apps are not bogus apps. They are quality apps with good reviews.All of the core apps that most people want are available for the Kindle Fire.WEB BROWSINGYes, you can browse the Web on the Kindle Fire. Do you really want to? For basic browsing, it's fine, but the screen is a bit small for it to be a great experience. In my opinion, apps are key with a tablet like the Kindle Fire. For example, instead of browsing Wikipedia, use an app designed for a smaller screen. Instead of browsing IMDB, use the built-in app on the Kindle Fire. Instead of browsing Amazon.com, use the built-in app for shopping at Amazon. These apps have a user-interface that is designed for a small screen, and the experience using them is first-rate.EMAILThe Kindle Fire comes with an email application that works well. It's not my first choice for email, but it'll do in a pinch.BOTTOM LINE:There are plenty of comparisons right now between the Nook Tablet and the Kindle Fire. Both are great devices, but the Kindle Fire's strength lies in the Amazon back end. In my book, no one can match Amazon's offerings in books, video, periodicals, and infrastructure. It's likely that Amazon will continue to improve upon these services in the future. The future for the competition (including B&N;) isn't quite so assured. Combine that with the $50 you save by going with the Kindle Fire, and the choice seems clear to me.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (6)

8 of 9 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsKindle Fire: Why are people complaining?,November 17, 2011By&nbsp;Stephanie Krasinski(Pittsburgh, PA)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)As someone who does not enjoy Apple products, period, perhaps I am a bit biased. Please consider that a disclaimer as you read this review.I have always said that the only way I would get a tablet is if Amazon made their own version. When I first read about the Kindle Fire, I was super excited. . .but then I realized I probably couldn't afford it. Yet I continued to torture myself by reading about it and essentially stalking it on Amazon.com. Eventually I ran into a deal that the Amazon.com Store Card was running: if you bought something $149+ and paid it off in full within 6 months of purchase, it would be interest free. That was all I needed and I instantly pre-ordered.First thing I want to address: I have read numerous review complaining about the Kindle Fire's weight and how it feels "clunky." This perplexes me. As much as I can understand the convenience of a lightweight object, why on Earth would you want to own something that felt as if you could break it? Perhaps it's because of my clumsy nature, but I much prefer something to feel sturdy and as though it can withstand use. The weight of the Kindle Fire is by no means going to cause pain on anyone or even make a difference in your purse/bag weight.Second thing: people discussed the speed, or lack thereof, of the browser. I'd have to say that might be related to their various WiFi connections, because I barely noticed any loading time. I ran Facebook, Amazon.com, a few games - all faster than, say, the connection on my work computer. I downloaded and purchased things within instants (again, faster than web pages load on my work computer).Third thing: people complained about not having direct e-mail integration; i.e.: a GMail app. I had absolutely no problems setting up my GMail and loading my contacts. Because I have an Android phone on which I have my Gmail account connected, even my phone contacts loaded.After reading the various reviews, I was the tiniest bit hesitant (should have known to trust Amazon) to start playing with it because I did not want to be disappointed. Within 20 minutes, though, I was in heaven and goofily grinning from ear-to-ear. This device is phenomenal, especially when you consider the price.  The one thing I will agree with from various reviews is this: if you want an iPad, shell out the $400+ for an iPad. But really, the Kindle Fire is the way to go. Thumbs up, Amazon - and thank you. :)Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

