ical folks (I'm more technical than most)The amazon app store does have a good selection and I've been able to find everything that I want or need via the store with one notable exception -- I could not get the Google+ app and have ended up using browser - not a real loss there. Also, I understand (through searches on the Internet) that the Android Market place has a broader selection. Amazon, however, may be working to address this.Now, the web browser -- amazing. I do feel the browser works well. I've been able to read forums that normally I cannot on the iPad or iPhone. Web pages come up fast enough and most important (from what I've seen) function as they should. I've had some issue with the iPad in this respect [but the websites are usually smaller, industry specific organization]I think it's an awesome grab at the price they are asking for... Hopefully this review was helpful.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

5 of 5 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsThe Kindle Fire,January 9, 2012By&nbsp;Vanity VonSyn-See all my reviewsThis review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I think that I have given myself enough time to play with the Fire before writing a review. I got a Kindle Fire for Christmas and I really like it. It by no means replaces the actual printed book. I am now reading my second e-book, the first was Charles Dickens "A Christmas Carol" and I do have to say that I do sort of miss the printed book. But printed books are what I am used to. I've never had an e-reader before now, so I'm still getting used to it. I really do like it though. It's terribly convenient. I can get really comfortable while reading in bed at night because I can prop it up on my blankets and not have to worry about it closing on me or the pages flipping on their own and me losing my place. I also don't have to reposition it or myself every time I turn a page, so I can see myself getting a bit spoiled to it, if I haven't already.I've read reviews where some people have complained about the weight of the Fire and honestly I don't see what all the complaints are about. I have hardcover books in my house that weigh either more or are about the same as the Fire. If you don't have any problems being able to carry around a thick hardcover book, then you won't have any trouble carrying around the Fire. Last week, my mother was reading a book called "Cemetery Dance" and out of curiosity, I picked it up in one hand and held the Fire in the other and I compared their weight. They were the same. So, I really don't see what all the complaints are about concerning the weight of the Kindle Fire. My high school Biology book weighed more than the Fire does. If you can carry a regular printed book with you, then you can carry the Fire. There is absolutely no difference.I don't like using the Fire for looking up anything in reference books. I was trying to look a word up in the dictionary on it earlier tonight and just from flipping through the pages page by page, apparently I kept hitting links to other words that are at the bottom of some of the pages. It kept putting me farther and farther away from the word that I had originally been trying to find. So I finally just gave up and decided that I would just use a printed dictionary to look the word up in. I can honestly find it a whole lot faster that way. That being said, the Dictionary desperately needs to have a "Search" feature to make it easier to look up specific words. I do like that the Fire allows you to be able to look up the meanings of words while you're reading. That is insanely helpful. A lot of times, I will come across words that I have never even heard of much less know the meanings of and it really helps to be able to look them up without interrupting your reading by having to go and drag out a big, heavy dictionary.I don't do much reading while outside because usually if I'm outside, I'm around other people and I find the noise to be too distracting. So most of my reading is done indoors. I have found that when outside with the Fire, the backlighting is usually not good for being able to see what you're looking at but with the Fire, you can change the background color of your pages (white is best when outside) and it helps to turn the screen brightness up a bit as well. I can do this and have no trouble being able to read while in the car during the day or while sitting inside of well-lighted buildings. Indoors, I tend to keep the screen brightness on its lowest possible setting, otherwise the brightness hurts my eyes to look at it.The wifi seems to be a bit glitchy. I don't know if it has had anything to do with the fact that it's been really cloudy today because of the rain last night but for some reason, it connected to my home internet for about three seconds earlier today and that was it. It immediately disconnected and I have been unable to get it to reconnect. Yet, none of the laptops that are in the house have had any trouble staying connected to the net today. Also, I thought that the wireless internet would work the same as it does with the laptops. But I have noticed that when I'm upstairs and the wifi is turned on, the internet connection comes and goes...often. It's like every couple of minutes its disconnecting. If I'm downstairs, it does better if I'm in the kitchen (I'm guessing this is because the kitchen is closer to the desktop which is the main computer where the network is and everything else it set up). When I'm in the living room, it's ok but it tends to come and go just not as often as it does upstairs. So I've been keeping it turned off unless I need to use it. A few days ago, I was attempting to check my e-mail and it worked great for a while, but at some point it just refused to load up any web page. It would take several minutes before giving me a white error page that said something along the lines of "Page Cannot Be Displayed" and no matter how many times I refreshed it or reloaded it in a different tab or closed it out all together and tried again it kept giving me the same thing. I even tried turning the Fire off completely and starting over. Eventually, I actually had to go to my laptop to finish what I had been doing. I don't know what the issue was but it finally stopped doing it though it took a few hours. The glitchy wireless internet is why I've given the Fire four stars rather than five. Otherwise, I would have easily given it five stars.The touch screen is really neat but it's definitely going to take some getting used to because I've never had a touch screen anything before. It's really easy when using the onscreen keyboard to repeatedly hit the wrong keys. It probably doesn't help that my finger nails tend to get in the way and pencil erasers don't seem to work on the touch screen either, so I'm pretty much stuck with using my fingers. I've had extra keys appear a few times and have no idea what I did to make them appear so I don't know how to make them do it again. I'm sure that I will figure it out eventually.You can highlight, copy and paste text which is really useful, especially when you can't remember your passwords and you have to copy and paste them. The copy and paste function is one that I am just starting to figure out. At first, I didn't even know that the Fire would let you and I was a bit disappointed. But since I've now learned that you can copy and paste text I've been pleasantly surprised. Good luck figuring that one out though without a mouse or a CTRL key.So far, I have been able to go to all of my usual web pages that I go to on my laptop. Google images works well. All of my e-mail (though I haven't checked my yahoo mail on it yet, yahoo's web messenger works well on the Fire) loads up and works well. Youtube works well. Overall, I have no complaints about the web browsing from the Fire. I just wish that the wireless internet on it would stay connected and stop coming and going. That's a little frustrating to have to deal with at times. Oh, you cannot play the games on MSN from the Fire. It says that the web browser is out of date. I read where someone asked the question as to whether you can play Farmville from the Fire. Yes, you can. But it's not the same as it is on a computer. You get the express version on the Fire. You don't actually go to your farm and you can't do anything other than harvest your crops and replant more. Several people have complained that the web browser is slow. It's not. If you want to know what "slow" is, get dial-up internet. That mess is painfully slow. Once you've had that for a while, you learn to appreciate faster internet connections. The web browser on the Fire is not slow at all. It's just as fast as my laptop is (I have DSL at my house). Someone else also said in a review that the sound through the speakers of the Fire is, in their words, "tinny". This is also not true. The sound is just fine to me. In fact, the sound from the Fire is actually better than the sound from my laptop. Listening to youtube on my laptop took some getting used to because the sound was just...not good. I can at least stand it now, so it's not so bad any more.I wasn't planning on using the Fire to watch movies or videos because I have a laptop and a portable DVD player for that. I also wasn't planning on using it to listen to a bunch of music because I have two MP3 players for that and they tend to go everywhere that I go. However, I have been considering putting some instrumental music on my Fire for reading purposes. It would help to drown out distracting background noise when my MP3 player needs recharging (yes, player rather than players because I only have, well nature sounds is what it is, on one of them). By the way, with the Fire only having, what is it, 8Gs? of space on it, if you start downloading movies, those 8Gs will get used up pretty quickly. Most movies are at least 500MB-700MB and I've seen some that are over 1G in file size. If you're going to watch movies on it, I would suggest streaming or deleting the movie after you've seen it. It really wouldn't hurt for the Fire to have more available space on it.Some people have complained that the battery life isn't long enough. It wouldn't hurt for the battery life to be as long as the other Kindles, but I honestly can't sit and read or play games for eight consecutive hours. So, eight hours is actually pretty good as far as I'm concerned. It'll last on trips where you have to spend at least six hours in the car and during long doctor's office visits. I've been doing most of my reading at night lately, so I've been having to recharge the Kindle at night before going to bed because by then the battery will be really low (I use it off and on throughout the day). And it's worked out nicely. It's finished charging by the time that I wake up in the morning and I am free to carry it around all over the place, which is what I do.One thing that has been consistent in every review that I have read for the Fire is that the power button is in a bad place. This is true. When I got my Fire for Christmas, I also got a leather case for it. The case really does help with the bad position of the power button. I have yet to accidentally turn the Fire off while reading or playing around with an app or whatever. The edge of the case keeps the power button from accidentally getting pushed while the Kindle is resting against your stomach or a pillow or whatever. So, I strongly suggest getting a case to put it in. It seems to have several benefits.Sadly, most of what I have read about the Fire has been complaints from people who seem to want to compare it to the iPad. It is NOT an inexpensive version of the iPad. If you want an iPad, then you need to shell out the $500+ to $800+ to get one rather than buying a Kindle Fire so that you can keep it for a week, send it back and complain about how you're disappointed because you didn't get what you wanted. The Kindle Fire is an e-reader with tablet capabilities. But it is NOT an iPad. I was researching the Fire before Christmas and it really annoyed me that 99% of what I had read about it was people complaining because it wasn't an iPad. I didn't want to know anything about the iPad; if I had have, I would have looked it up. What I wanted to know about was the Kindle Fire. I didn't really care to read peoples' whining over the iPad. I do read the reviews that people give things and when you're supposed to be giving a review for a specific item, it really helps everyone else out if you review that item rather than picking it apart with complaints about something else. So, please, if you all you're going to do is whine because you wanted an iPad, go whine about it somewhere else. I, for one, am very pleased with the Kindle Fire and I won't be returning it. I'd like to keep it. It does what it was advertised to be able to do and because of this, I am content. I do wish that you could bookmark PDF files though and I do miss my page numbers. But other than that and the seemingly glitchy wireless internet, I'm perfectly content with it.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (7)

