5 of 5 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsAffordable Tablet for the Average 'Joe',January 3, 2012By&nbsp;Timothy L. Wagner "DaddyWags"(Chicago, IL USA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)You've probably seen a lot of reviews by 'experts', including PC World, CNET, etc.  Here's the perspective of a 50 something family man who works on a laptop and loves his old Kindle.I decided on the Fire for a Christmas present from the family as I really did not need much, and being a gadget guy, I was intrigued by the low price point and the integration of an app-based device with a Kindle system. Being a Prime Member, I also liked the thought of having movies for free, and the availability of the Kindle Lenders Library.So, how is it?-If you have an existing Kindle, you know the out of the box pleasure of having things all set up. The Fire is the same way. Your account, your existing library, etc. is all THERE! So, from the first minute you're able to get back to the latest book you're reading.-Apps: I worried, after using an IPod Touch, that the app availability would be limited, especially since you do not have direct access to the Android store. It's true that you can't get to that store, but the number of apps currently for the Fire via Amazon's Android store is impressive. No, they didn't have my current favorite (Bookworm), but they did have a clone. All the best apps are there though, from Netflix to Angry Birds. In fact, let's face it, no one has the time to look at 10,000 apps, so having 5,000 to look through is still a ton. Plus, Amazon is adding them all the time. There's also a free app of the day, that is actually the paid versions of some pretty good apps.-Movies/Video: With both Netflix and Prime Movies available, the movie titles are great. Watching on the Fire is actually a nice experience. You'll need headphones, but the sound is crisp and the screen is lovely. My wife has recently been watching in bed and I may have to be purchasing a second Fire soon.-Web: Web access is fine. Is it slower then Chrome? Firefox? Yes, a little. But the difference is not that big a deal. You can get on all your favorite websites, set favorites, etc.-Books: Reading a book with a backlit screen is different then reading one on the Pearl-Ink non-lit screens of the standard Kindle. You can now read without an external light, and that's sweet. The bad news? Battery life is around 8 hours, so you'll have to plug in for recharging more. Access to the Kindle store (and our local Library) was the same on the Fire as the old Kindle, but enhanced by the color screen.-Magazines/Newspapers: Wow. Just...wow. I occasionally read news off my laptop, but being an old fashioned guy, I still like the morning paper. I may stop now. The 7" touch color screen makes reading the paper with a cup of coffee easy. One finger can move from page to page, story to story. I can hold it in one hand, it's light, and I don't have to worry about getting up and down with a laptop on my legs. Magazines are beautiful on the Fire.  You can zoom in if you need it (adjust text size and font just like the old Kindle), but I forgot how much I missed color until I started using the Fire as an e-reader. Even the dust jackets of my books stand out.  The Fire comes with an app called 'Pulse'. Take time to check it out. It's an aggregator, i.e., it takes news and pics from information sources you pick out and puts it in a flick book like environment that makes browsing for stories a joy.Cons-7" is smaller then the 10" IPad, but you know what? Who cares. I can carry this thing in my Parka pocket. I can pull it out on the train and read. It has no 3G, so is Wi-Fi dependent for accessing the web. It won't replace a smart phone, but let's be honest, do you web surf that much on your phone with your own data plan charging you all the time? Wi-Fi is everywhere, so it's not that big a drawback to me.  Storage: A lot of made about storage, and it's smaller then the IPad or Nook. However, it's still likely more then you'll ever use.Pros-Everything. This is the tablet for the 'rest of us'. Cheap, well made, pretty, and flexible. It's a gamechanger.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

