7 of 8 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsFrom an actual owner,December 21, 2011By&nbsp;L. Harris "LHarris"(Lincoln, NE, USA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I finally gave in and got my Fire, and I have to say it's easily as good as the positive reviews claim, with only a few of the flaws from the nay-sayers.Pros:-It runs Android. This ties in a bit with the cons (more later), but since under the heavily modified surface, Android is still there and can be modified to your own liking. It takes a little bit of know-how, but can easily be modified by anyone who cares to try. This gets into all kinds of additional options of customization that I won't go into here.-It's FAST. I haven't had any problems with freezing, unresponsive touches, or sluggish loading. The first few days I used the built in Silk browser, which performed quite well, but I have since switched to Dolphin HD due to interface and personal preferences. The Fire itself seems to have great battery life, but I still charge it nightly, as I do out of habit with all of my gadgets.-The size seems perfect. It's easy to hold in one hand and navigate, and is convenient to slip into a messenger bag without taking up much space. I did get a case for my FireTimbuk2 Kindle Fire CUSH SLEEVE, Gunmetal/Limeaidand I'm not worried at all about damaging it. I also like the rubberized back, which gives a little more texture to hold onto and prevents it from slipping if propped up on a table. Plus, it's one less surface to get smudged up by fingerprints!-Wifi manager is clean, fast, and simple to use. I might recommend an app, Wifi Analyzer, which pairs well with the built in connection wizard.-The display is sharp! It can be quite bright, but allows a wide range of adjustment for various situations. I find that the 7" display is plenty for typical usage. If you need more, then you're probably not using the Fire for the intended purposes. Browsing most websites, checking email, reading magazines and books all work quite well on this display size (IMHO).-The speakers sound respectable, considering the size of the device. They're hardly audiophile quality, but they put out a decent level without distorting.Cons:-More of a quirk...but when you're watching a movie on the Fire, having speakers on only one side is unbalanced. It would have been nice to separate them so the audio is balanced on both sides (when not using headphones).-Built in "carousel" interface is cludgy. I don't care much for it personally, especially when loading other apps that don't display well on the shelf. However, if you use GO Launcher as an alternative, this is a non-issue!-No hard volume buttons. I'll adjust, and it's not that big of a deal, but it would be nice to adjust the volume on the fly when listening to music.-It's a little on the heavy side. It's lighter than the iPad, and smaller obviously, but since it can easily be held with one hand, it's possible that it may get a little heavy during extended use.-Amazon's lockdown on the Android market and apps is annoying. There are ways around it, but I'm not interested in rooting an otherwise great device. With a little bit of research and minimal work, it's easy enough to side-load some extra apps, but it would REALLY be nice if Amazon could get a deal worked out with Google. The Fire runs Android and supports a lot of apps, but it's frankly absurd that more aren't even allowed.Overall, the Fire is definitely what I expected. Regardless of how good a gadget is when I buy it, I always love to fiddle with it and customize as much as possible. With the Fire, it takes only half of a brain cell more than usual, but I'm quite happy with how it works. The size, features, power, and convenience are all great, and with the low price tag, I have absolutely no regrets and will definitely be recommending it to anyone.Help other customers find the mos