9 of 11 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsMore than what I'd hoped for.,December 19, 2011By&nbsp;M. Rupp(Eau Claire, WI)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Firstly, I just want to start off by saying that this device ought to be researched before people purchase it; the reason being is that too many people give it poor reviews for things they could have known about before hand.  I am a college student with a laptop and just a plain old cell phone (not a smart phone).  I mention this because I am just an average joe consumer in terms of tech gadgets.  Having researched the Kindle Fire, I thought that for 199 dollars, it was a great deal for what it could do. After receiving the Fire, I was very impressed with its capabilities.The display is absolutely gorgeous and the Web Browser is great.  I have great loading speeds and the browser actually lets you choose in many cases if you want the tablet or normal version of their webpage but in almost every case, the web pages look how they would on a pc.  The Netflix, Hulu, and Pandora apps are great free starter apps along with tons more stuff.  So far, I've downloaded like twenty apps and paid for about three or four of them.  Not to mention the six books I got that were free to download.  I can't stress enough how crisp the display is; videos from Netflix come in with amazing clarity.So obviously, no, the Fire is not an Ipad 2.  It's also not 500 dollars.  If what you're looking for is a tablet to use with wifi as a general reading/entertainment device, I highly recommend the Fire.  The memory space could be larger of course but I don't really use my Kindle for music at all as I have a Ipod Nano but I do use it for video.  You could store something like four DVD quality movies on it at a time (which would be more than enough for a flight) or about one or two HD movies.  As I said though, I use my Kindle to watch Netflix and Hulu, as well as surf the web, read the news, check the weather, and other similar tasks.  The Kindle Fire has been an absolute blast so far and I really only have two critiques of it.Firstly, when you buy the Fire, buy a micro USB to USB cable with it if you don't have one already; they are like five bucks and you need one to download movies to your Kindle unless you only use the Amazon video feature.  But to the actual critique, the Fire can only read MP4 video format.  This means that any video you want to store on the Kindle has to be in MP4.  This is sort of a hassle but there are free converters like freemake that allow you to convert videos to MP4's if you want to save them on the Fire.  I'm not a 'give me convenience or give me death' kind of guy so for me this wasn't a big deal, but I would love to be able to save movies from the web directly to my Kindle (which you still can so long as they're MP4).  Don't worry about streaming videos, they all work fine.My only other criticism is the lack of ability to configure the home start up page.  The Fire currently saves the app history right on the home menu so whatever you've opened last will pop up, along with the previous app and so on.  What you can do though, for people worried about their browser history for the web, is to hit the little cog up in the right corner, select more, select applications, and finally select the Amazon browser.  From here you can clear the cache and all data which essentially deletes the web history.  Conversely, try not looking at porn if you don't want your wife/girlfriend/kids to discover you.  But as far as the home menu is concerned, I was hoping I could set up the menu to show what I wanted instead of just showing my app history by default.  There may even be a way to fix this but as of yet I haven't found out how.  I have heard the Fire is supposed to have some big updates coming in late December that may even fix a thing or two including what I mentioned.If what you're looking for is an affordable Tablet for leisure/entertainment purposes, I highly recommend the Fire.  I got it about 1 1/2 weeks ago and I still get excited when I come home and remember I have my Fire on the nightstand.  I wake up to read the news in bed with it and watch an episode on Netflix before I go to bed at night.  I love it and if you want a really fun, affordable tablet then feel confident in buying a Fire.  Just make sure you've done you're research on it so you know what it does and does not do.  If you buy ANYTHING before researching it and it doesn't do what you thought, that's on you, not the product.  If you've researched it and it sounds like a great device, I would say pull the trigger for sure.  I love the Fire and it exceeded my expectations.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

