9 of 11 people found the following review helpful3.0 out of 5 starsProblem with Parental Controls,May 4, 2012By&nbsp;Big Don-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Last night while using my Kindle Fire, a popup said that the Parental Controls are on and I could not access the internet.  The popup had a place to enter my password to get on the internet.  Since I did not have a password and had not ever set up parental controls there was no way to bypass this request.  Additionally, the fine print under the password request box said that if you forgot your password you will have to do a factory reset of your entire Kindle Fire and register it again and download and set up all your apps again.  Not wanting to believe that was my only option, thinking there must be another option like all other computers if you forget your password  I contacted Amazon technical services. The people at tech services were very helpful and courteous but told me there is no other options which meant I had to go through the factory reset and reset up everything on my Kindle Fire.  This morning I got an email from Amazon advising me that they had updated my Kindle with parental controls and that if you put in the wrong password 4 times you must do a factory reset.  Word to the Kindle user, check and see if you have parental controls on your Kindle.  Make sure you create a password for the parental controls, if you don't you may run into the same problem I had with the popup. If you don't have a parental control password, you will need to perform a factory reset on your Kindle Fire to access the internet.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment (1)

