9 of 11 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsExcellent Tablet for the Price (Non-Techy Review),December 1, 2011By&nbsp;PixelPi-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)This review is for ordinary folks: I am not a gadget geek or computer whiz -- and this is my first experience with a tablet device. If you're looking for technical details, business uses, and/or comparison with other devices, this review is not for you. If you've never owned a tablet and are reasonably familiar with PC use (email, surfing the web, games, etc.), you've come to the right place!I've been using my Fire now for about 2 weeks, and truthfully I very little negative to say about it. A tablet has been on my mind for quite a while, but the steep prices held me back -- until the Kindle Fire was announced at what seemed to be a bargain-basement price. I couldn't resist, and I'm very happy that I took the plunge.There is no paper user manual included with the Fire. Using the device straight out of the box is fairly intuitive for people (like me) who feel comfortable using PC email, browsing, and game software packages, and there is an online users manual. The display is crisp, colors terrific, and volume adequate. The screen is very glossy and reading in direct sunlight is difficult. Although it's considerably heavier than the Kindle, the Fire handles easily. It does run a bit warm after being used for a prolonged period of time, but has not overheated yet. Battery life is good, but runs down fairly quickly when wi-fi is being used. It recharges quickly, however.  If you've never used a computer at all, the lack of documentation might be problematic. The Fire does not have a camera, which is fine by me as I use a digital camera for photographs.There are plenty of apps available and many of them are free. I have about 30 apps loaded on my Fire, and all of them run with no problems. Setting up magazine apps to read my paper subscriptions online was easy, and they allow new dimensions for magazine articles such as video demos of recipes and crafts, etc. There are more game apps than I could ever want or use. There are also productivity apps available for the Fire such as word processing and spreadsheets, which I personally don't need.The Fire does require users to have their own wi-fi connection or a wi-fi connection at a "hot spot" -- there is no free 3G (as with the Kindle), and I would be surprised if 3G is ever included with the Fire. I think Amazon would find it prohibitively expensive to offer free 3G for customers who would be downloading large files. The Kindle has free 3G because even the most expensive e-books only take seconds to download, in contrast to the movies and web sites accessible to Fire users.I am very satisfied with the Fire and very happy to have spent $199 for such a good product. I would definitely reccomend it to others (and have already purchased another Fire as a gift).I have used the Amazon Prime membership to view streaming videos, and for me the variety and quality of movies and television shows is more than adequate. The streaming is smooth and seamless, with volume levels easily adjustable and plenty loud without earbuds.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

