4 of 4 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsShort Realistic Review,January 10, 2012By&nbsp;Mike-See all my reviewsThis review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Gonna make this short and sweet because this device has a lot of aspects that could be addressed that will lose you attention.I'm a techie, I work for a Media Services firm and Root Cellphones on the side, just giving you some perspective on my review.THE BADThe operating system is a skin on an outdated version of android, so don't expect a god device, it's 200 bucks and you get what you pay for. It has glitches, it lags when switching orientations, and like any android device some apps can wreck its speed. If you have major speed issues with your kindle, uninstall the last couple apps you installed and it will likely be back to slightly glitchy. That being said, TAKE CARE OF YOUR DEVICE! Don't install every app in the world and expect it to run like your quad core 8gb ram computer! I have had a couple of freezes, but honestly I was expecting it, this is not an iPad, it has 70% of the features of an iPad at 40% of the price. That's why you get this, and you love it like I do.The biggest bother I have with the device is the touch screen. I love touch screens, and in 5 years everything will have them. But this one is sub par, not "bad" per-say, but sub par. On OCCASION I find myself pressing two or three times to get the device to register a click. Along with that the hidden buttons (which I'll get to later) are hard to access sometimes because I can't get the accuracy required to hit the sliver of the screen you need to touch to get to them.Wifi is a pain sometimes and using the quick settings widget for wifi causes it to force close frequently, but because I rarely change my wifi connection because i'm on a college campus littered with hotspots of the same SSID I don't have to.So far I have not found a way to add a microphone to the device. I have attempted using headphones with a mic built in, but the button for pausing music doesn't even work. Now that could be a software thing, as the device is not designed to have that button or mic, the programming does not include protocol for button click or mic sound.There is no native drop box app yet. You will have to install the easily downloadable .apk file manually after installing a file browser. Easy if you have any experience or know how to use a search engine (google, bing etc).THE GOODNOW, when you get into an app, away from the "bookshelf" this device is awesome. The dual core 1ghz processor is blazing fast, I have not yet been hindered by processing speed and I'm loving it. The screen is bright and crisp. The battery life is true to its word, according to my battery monitor app, I'm getting an average of 10 hours of use and I'm using this thing CONSTANTLY, maybe not constant video streaming, but the display is really what sucks power, so turn the brightness below 80% to get this awesome battery life.The lack of physical buttons is the future, just look at Ice Cream Sandwich (latest version of Android). I love it, it makes extra room on the device for more screen without making the screen larger.The speakers were surprising, very loud and decent sound quality.I love using this for music, it will play any music on your amazon cloud player, be it purchased from Amazon or ripped from cd's or even downloaded from elsewhere. I have however had difficulty uploading files purchased from iTunes, but that's not surprising, that's why I left iTunes a couple years ago.I LOVE LOVE LOVE the design of the tablet, the rubber back is perfect for gripping the device (unlike metal which gets cold and easily slips out of your hand). I do wish the power button was on the top, but if you really have an issue with that, turn the device upside down, it can work from any angle. If you thought the button was supposed to be on top, it is. There is no difference in holding it upside down.THE ENDWell I went on a little longer than I wanted to, but what I said is important. Key things to take away from this. Inexpensive, Good Design/Craftsmanship, Sub Par Operating System, Good Media Consumption.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

