4 of 4 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsKindle Fire Review,December 17, 2011By&nbsp;Cantatta-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)The Kindle Fire is a great product for what it does.  What it does is deliver Amazon digital content, and I think it does this pretty well.  Is it the best device on the market?  No.  Is it a direct competitor to the iPad?  No.  However, the Fire is a great product, none the less.  While not being a full functional touch-screen tablet, it does most of the things that other tablets do.  It is Android based, with a little research you can Root the Fire and open it up so that it functions more like a true tablet.  You never truly own an Android device until it's Rooted.All of your content appears on the main screen in the order of most recently viewed or used.  This applies equally to web pages and e-books, videos and documents.  Each item is represented by an icon, and all of the icons appear in a flip-file or rolodex fashion. You just flip through the list until you find what you want.  The downside to the flip-file setup is that there is no security or privacy.  Whoever uses the Kindle Fire will be able to see exactly what the last person was doing.  You cannot change or remove items from this list, and there is no way to setup multiple users with different lists.  As long as you aren't doing anything wrong, or you don't share, this shouldn't be a problem.Additionally, on the main screen there are menu choices at the top, most of which are simple filters for the content you have on your Kindle.  There is also a clock and a settings menu at the upper-right of the main screen. You can choose between Videos, Docs, Web, Apps, etc. When you choose to view one particular item type, you choose further filters that will sort according to most recent or alphabetic, for instance.  It might be nice to have more choices for sorting, but the availble options work well enough.  There is a back-arrow at the bottom of the screen that will take you back to the previou screen, or back to the main menu, depending on where you are in the menu structure or inside an app.  There is also a Home button, represented buy a house icon, which will always take you back to the main menu from anywhere.As an e-reader, the Kindle Fire is as good as any other on the market. Gone is the E-Ink screen of the other Kindle devices. The color multi-touch screen funtions well, with plenty of sensitivity and good response and feel.  Occasionally, you have to press something twice before the Fire responds, so there is definitely room for improvement here.  Even so, the screen displays vivid color and high resolution graphics and video.  I find it easy to read web pages, e-books and PDFs.  Zoom functions allow you to get up close for fine print, if needed, and the zoom function is pretty snappy.  Navigating different digital documents is easy and intuitive, and the Fire loads them up pretty quickly.  I bought a DC comic book to see how it handles that kind of media, and it does a fantastic job.  You can zoom into individual frames on each page to get a nice closeup of the artwork and the text, but you can also read the comic just fine without zooming in, too.I had a little trouble viewing some streaming content on the Kindle Fire, but it was mostly with Amazon video content. Installing the Netflix app and streamuing from their service has been working much better, though I think there is room for improvment with the video streaming, just the same.  Most of the time the video looks great, but occasionally it gets blurry and pixilated.  This could be a bandwidth issue and not the fault of the Kindle Fire, I need to test streaming in more locations to be sure.  While not the most polished feature, streaming media does work on the Fire, and I have watched quite a few movies and TV shows on mine.  The screen provides a sharp, clear picture, though again, this will sometimes depend on bandwidth available on your wireless service. It is important to note that all tablets, PCs and smart phones are subject to this problem, not just the Fire.  The more bandwidth you have, the better streaming media will look and sound, no matter what device you are using.The Amazon App store is your sole source for apps on the Kindle Fire, unless you Root the Fire and install the Android Market manually.  The selection in the Amazon Market isn't as vast as that of the Android Market or iTunes Store yet, but there are a lot of good apps out there for the Fire, even so.  And something I don't think either of the other two offer at all, Amazon Market offers one free App every day.  This includes apps that you normally have to pay for.  I have gotten a few gems this way and often check in daily to see what's available.  I like this feature so much, I added Amazon Market to my Android smart phone.I will admit the price for the Kindle Fire influenced my decision to purchase.  I have wanted a Kindle since they first came out.  By the time they became cheap enough for me to consider buying one, rumors were floating around about a color Kindle, so I decided to wait.  The day the Kindle Fire was announced, I orderd one.  The price was right and I knew that it would do a lot more than a standard Kindle.  However, I never thought the Kindle Fire was going to replace the iPad or other tablets.  It isn't really designed to do that.  However, as I said before, it does what it's designed to do pretty well, in my opinion.The Kindle Fire could use some improvements, no doubt about it, but for the price, there isn't anything better available right now.  Amazon is planning an update in the near future, we'll have to see what is in store for the Kindle Fire.  As it stands, I'm pretty happy with my purchase of a Kindle Fire.  It does everything I want it do, and it does most of it pretty darn well.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

