4 of 4 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsADD Enabler.,December 10, 2011By&nbsp;Gary Perry "Gary"(Opelika, AL USA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Perhaps the worst part of the Kindle fire is that it is an enabler for ADD.Someone described the Kindle Fire as a media consumption device. This is very true. Once you get a Fire in your hands you will not be able to decide what you want to do. You can easily read books, there are more free books available than you'll have time to read. You'll be able to read documents you have uploaded, read magazines in full color, watch TV episodes you've missed or haven't been able to see on cable. You'll have more movies than you have time to watch especially if you sign up for Amazon Prime. What's even worse is that you get a month's free membership in Amazon Prime. Of course if all else fails for lack of interest you can surf the web. The Fire does a very good job of rendering pages even if they're not optimized for mobile devices.With that somewhat tongue in cheek review, though still true, let me give you some advice. If you have a Kindle e-reader, keep it. You will want both. I was a little disappointed at first with the Fire because I expected it to replace either my Kindle e-reader or my laptop PC or both. It won't do either. Contrary to what some people have said I do believe it to be an iPad killer. So far I haven't found anything the Fire won't do that an iPad will. Keep in mind that the iPad does have 3G and a built in camera but I don't need either of those. You will want to keep your Kindle e-reader because there is absolutely nothing better to keep in your glove box or pocket to pull out and read while you're waiting in line or waiting on your wife to finish shopping. If you write a lot you will want to keep your laptop because you can't beat a full-size keyboard but chunk the laptop and get a new one if the screen is smaller than 17". You'll prefer the Fire for anything smaller. You can upload your documents to your Fire and edit them there.I made the mistake of giving my daughter my Kindle e-reader. I plan to rectify that situation as soon as I get my Amazon Gift Cards for Christmas. I will be purchasing the $79 e-reader. That's another good point. If you are particularly difficult to buy gifts for you now have the perfect gift to tell all your friends and relatives. Amazon Gift Cards are the perfect accessory to the Fire.This brings up a couple of accessories that are a must have. You will want to purchase the Pro version of Quick Office. That's a must if you want to edit documents. Secondly, the screen is too reflective, glare is a problem. You'll want an anti-glare screen. You'll also want a small USB cable to connect to your laptop to upload documents directly to the Fire. Don't try to send them through the Amazon email. You won't be able to edit documents sent through the kindle.com email. You'll want to purchase a set of earbuds if you don't already have them. You can watch movies and videos discreetly at the office or traveling without disturbing anyone else. Lastly you'll want the fold up cover that acts as a stand. For standing the Fire is small enough to hold in one hand but if you can sit it on a desk or table that is much more comfortable.All of the changes I would like to see revolve around the operating system. Personally I do not like the carousel. I would prefer to be able to delete that and use the apps screen as my home page. Secondly, the Fire ships with some apps on it that can't be deleted. IMDB for one. There should be some way to delete apps from the cloud setting on the Fire. The Fire should be shipped locked or unregistered. The Post Office delivered my Fire to the wrong address but luckily I got it back. I found once I opened it that it was ready to order anything off my Amazon account with one click. I read a review where another customer had a Fire misdelivered and ended up with over $300 in charges before they could stop it.The fact that the Fire has limited storage and WiFi will need to be managed. By managed I mean that when you take the Fire away from WiFi you will need to decide before you leave the WiFi connection which movies, videos and songs you want to store within the Fire since it only has approximately 6 GB of storage available for use. You won't be able to stream from Amazon Prime while you're in transit from one hotspot to another.Future updates I'd like to see include the changes to the operating system I mentioned above and a USB connector or port to allow the use of SD cards. That would solve the memory problem altogether and it already has a mini USB port available for recharging and connecting to the PC. It should be a simple matter to have a mini USB connector on a Memory stick reader. A dongle with a mini USB connector on one end and a female USB connector on the other for Flash Drives is an option. The ability to read SD cards seems to be built in but until an SD card can be plugged in that is speculation.Lastly, I can't give the Fire a 5 star rating simply because it is not perfect. It is close but it does need the changes and accessories I mentioned.One last bit of advice that doesn't cost anything at all. As soon as you get your Fire in your hands, change the security setting to where it is locked and password protected. As an added precaution because I'm paranoid, add virus protection.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

4 of 4 people found the following review helpful2.0 out of 5 starsAntenna warning/customer service warning,December 12, 2011By&nbsp;H. Stevens(Crownsville, MD USA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I wanted to love this.  I DID love it the first time I turned it on and connected flawlessly to the wifi in my house.  I watched  a movie. I browsed the web.  I downloaded a game.  I relished the lightweight sleek design.Then I moved to a room that was more than ten feet from my wireless router.  My Kindle fire became just an overpriced reader, because the connection (at 15 feet!) was so tenuous that nothing that needed an internet signal could be used.All the hours spent on discussion boards, all the attempts at resets and reboots and moving of the router... ...all to no avail.  My call to customer service was equally as frustrating.  The CS rep was clearly working from a script and, since Amazon's script didn't include any acknowledgement that there could be a design flaw (which MANY frustrated buyers have reported in hindsight, I now see...) having to do with the antenna, I was simply told, in the end, "Thank you for letting us know.  We will report your issue to the development department."  No offer to replace.  No suggestion of what to do, at all.  The implication seemed to be that I should be content with the ten foot reception range.Really, Amazon?  Really?  You didn't try very hard on this one.If you order, be sure to thoroughly check out the wireless reception in every room of your house that works with other devices.  Do it before your 30 day return window closes.  Hope your experience is better than mine!Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment (1)

4 of 4 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsPeople need to get a grip on reality,December 12, 2011By&nbsp;Daniel Morris-See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I've made very few reviews in my time, but after reading a bit of very bizarre reviews about the Kindle Fire, I felt I had to speak up.There is this constant need to compare everything to iPads, but they aren't remotely the same device, nor are they in the same price-class.  I have a Honda Accord that cost me about $22k.  Do you see me writing up reviews about how it just doesn't hold up to the $66,000 Mercedes SUV?Please.  What is wrong with people?If someone is such a little hipster that they can't hold any electronic appliance without comparing it to an Apple product that costs three times as much, perhaps they shouldn't dirty their little hands.  I just got through being told how I was a fool to buy my little toshiba laptop instead of a macbook.... only to find out that the guy had paid THREE TIMES AS MUCH for his mac book.  Sorry, but I can't afford to be that cool if the one that costs 75% less does the same job.Believe it or not, I actually HAVE and iPad.  (eeekkk!!)I like it, but it is just a bit too big for what I need.  I read a lot and I have an infant.  So, for me to rock a baby to sleep and read means I need a paperback, or something I can hold in on hand and turn the pages with my thumb.  -&gt; Kindle.Can't do it with an iPad.  Sorry Mac fans, but i need my ipad to be smaller, there's no App for that.I also carry around a ton of junk wherever I go and my kindle actually fits in my back pocket.  (yep, it does).  I keep my books on it.  I read on the bus, on BART, at the Caffe, wheverver I have to wait.  Pulling it out of my back pocket is a one-handed maneuver.I used to use my phone to read on, but now I've got the Fire.Maybe a Nook would work too, probably, but I've used the nook and the Fire is a bit better.  I'd say that it is fare to compare the Nook to the Fire, but anyone comparing the Fire to an iPad is someone who's already biased towards the iPad.  No person with a actual clue about reality would compare the two unless they were making a point that the Fire could probably take care of 80% of what people actually do on their iPads.In fact, the only "threat" that the Fire ever held towards the iPad was that most iPad users actually would have been satisfied with a much more basic tablet, therefore the iPad absorbed many sales that it shouldn't have had in the first place, but gained only due to the fact that there was no product to cover that market sector.Now, just to get off the iPad irritation, I also want to point out that some people have kids.  I have 3.  They break stuff constantly.  They love to delete things.I've already had one iPad disaster, I'm not going to have another.  With that little kindle, I pop a movie in and hand it to my 5yr old and she can drive it with no problem.  My 3yr old has already tossed it down a flight of stairs -not a scratch.  She left it outside all day in the son - no problem.  I've sat on it a number of times (back pocket).  So far the thing is a rock.  And if it breaks, seriously, it isn't all that big a deal.  When that iPad got fried, all my pics that hadn't been sycned up were hosed.  I lost a ton of crap (yes, my own fault, but think about it.  I didn't have an option to leave them unsupervised, and now I do.)If you're going to get a table for $199, there is simply nothing on the market that is remotely close to this.  period.  nothing.It isn't perfect.  There's all sorts of crap that I'd like to change, but for $199, it rocks.There is nothing even close to the capabilities for that price.  nothing.  not even close.And, if you do have $600.... think about exactly what you "need" before you drop it all on an iPad.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&