4 of 4 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsMay not be perfect but a great device,November 17, 2011By&nbsp;Innisai-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I ordered Fire as soon as it was announced and was eagerly waiting for its arrival for more than a month. Though I was slightly disappointed with some of the early reviews, within a few minutes of using the device, I realized that they all were wrong to dismiss Fire as an average device. Few call Fire as Kindle with additional features, but I am not afraid to call it as a Tablet. Not all the tablets have to have front facing camera - of course, it's good to have but its absence does not make Fire any little. I am not going to go in detail with comparison here but features and flaws.Some of the + points:1) PriceThough I don't want to use the price point alone to recommend this product over other features, but it's worth pointing out. Like many of you, I too have owned tens of gadgets but not many times I have felt so happy to get an "useful" gadget in this price range. I loved using iPhone - I bought it for $700 on the 2nd day with no contract - but I could not stop thinking how expensive it was. Even iPod touch costs around $200.2) Colors, Fonts and controls.I have not owned an android device before so I am not sure how much Fire resembles other Android devices in terms of Fonts and Colors. But Fire looks so refreshing with the dark gray and orange colors. Beautiful! I also like the overall UX of Fire software (Easy to navigate, organize, control apps). Initially I was annoyed by the fact that I could not change the music while in other applications. Later I figured out that I could tap on the system tray (Where notifications, system time are displayed) to achieve that. It's pretty cool.3) Out of Box experience:I was surprised to see my name displayed as soon as I was done with initial setup (or even before, I don't exactly remember). I did not have to enter my name, user id, password. Everything was right there. Amazon has an advantage in this case because they are being both the seller as well as manufacturer. However, there are few other companies but how many of them do that?.4) Cloud experience:Many may have already pointed this out. I was easily able to sync my MP3s from Amazon and instantly watch prime videos with no issues.5) Connecting to PC:I like that, unlike iTunes, I have the freedom to access the files through USB mass storage. I was able to copy Music, PDFs, Pictures to Fire with no issues. I like not having a bloatware to take care of transferring contents. It will also be helpful to copy files from any computer to the device or from the device to any other computer.6) Decent set of AppsNot all the apps are available, but I found most of the apps I regularly use. It comes with the decent Mail client that helped me setup Gmail. It also claims that it has Unified Inbox but I have not tried setting up another email account.Mint, Texas Poker, Social apps, Adobe are the few others. It also comes with built in Amazon app which is easy to use and, as Amazon like you to do, purchase. I was even able to find an app to handle Microsoft Exchange email accounts but I have yet to set it up.7) DocumentsReading experience is smooth. Built in reader handles PDF documents much better than Adobe reader can.9) TouchFew earlier reviews pointed out that touch experience was not good. But I feel that touch is actually good. It's smooth except in few scenarios - it depends on the application. If you are navigating the home screen or looking at the contents from your device - for e.g. reading a document - it's fine. I noticed that when a cloud app (like App Store) is used, it feels sluggish but in other places, it's alright. I believe that it's got more to do with the way apps cache the items and images.Few drawbacks:1) Apps:As I mentioned above, not all the apps are available yet. I could not find a decent messenger for Live or GTalk. I believe that this will get improved during next few months. Some of the apps have been poorly ported. For e.g. Kama (I guess I have spelled it correct) Texas Poker, is one of the popular poker apps in iOS devices. But it looks horrible in Fire. It's not well scaled and the placement of buttons like "Call", "Raise", is worse. In iOS, it makes sense because there's no system controls in the bottom of the screen (Landscape) but in Fire, bottom of the screen is where you find the controls to go to the Home Screen or to go back to the previous screen. Not only those buttons were placed right above the system controls, in spite of bigger screen, the size of the buttons are still small - just like iOS versions - and makes it very hard to preciously touch them.With in-built Amazon app, I had difficulties placing an order - it was continuously asking me to sign in. I had to eventually use Web Browser to complete the order.2) BrowserI like browsing in 7" screen compared to my iOS devices. However, browser feels partially done. Not only is it slow but it sometimes does not render things correctly.For instance, while signing up an email account through Live, I had to tap and type on the same text box multiple times in order to enter the user name. It took me more than a few minutes to complete the page.3) VideoIt does not seem to play MP4 or other video formats.4) PC transfer rateTransfer rate is much slower than other devices. iTunes to iOs devices is much faster.5) MagazineI could not find WSJ on Fire. I thought that it was available in Fire but unfortunately not.6) Language supportI noticed that support (browser rendering) for few languages are missing.Other than these minor nuisances, I am a happy Fire owner and am looking forward to Fire 2nd generation with these issues fixed, front facing camera and Skye, Google apps for 199$ :-)Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this 