4 of 4 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsAwesome For $200, Minor Issues Can Hopefully be Corrected in TIme,November 17, 2011By&nbsp;Princess B-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)The Kindle Fire is a $200 (forked) android tablet. It is not a $500 iPad. Do not make the mistake of thinking that it is, and you'll run less risk of being disappointed.We have two Fires. Both on the same account, which means we share all purchases. If you're in a family, I can't stress how important that is! Registering Kindles to different accounts means you can't share books (outside of lending) and apps. So make sure that if you DO have multiple in your household, you order them on one account!The free month of Prime upgraded our conditional Prime account (Amazon Mom) to include streaming of a large selection of movies and TV shows. This is a welcome addition to our Netflix account (the app for which we reviewed at 4 stars due to minor issues with playback volume which can hopefully be fixed) as it has a different selection. We will, no doubt, be paying for Prime at this rate. (And will be checking out the Kindle Lending Library as well, of course.)The Fire's touchscreen is fairly responsive and of course suffers from the OMG SO DIRTY issue that all touchcscreens have. Using a microfiber cloth regularly helps this a bit. While not as large as a 10-inch tablet, the Fire's 7-inches are sufficient for email, twitter, facebook, app usage, playing games, reading books, etc. I've had no real issues reading full-size manual PDFs on it, though that does require use of the two-finger zoom function. In addition it is quite portable and much lighter than a 10-inch tablet. (Though nowhere near as light as our Kindle keyboard, of course.)I would give the Fire 5 stars, as we are absolutely loving them, were it not for some minor issues with the details. A few examples of niggling issues include applications that are listed as being available on the Fire (all of which are supposed to be curated) which either do not install or do not function. We have not PAID for an app and had it fail yet, but I am willing to bet that it's possible to do so, at which point you'll need to get in touch with Customer Support in order to seek reimbursement. The keyboard is "ok" but could perhaps be improved upon. Organizing books (such as into a series) and documents (like by project) is a non-starter as there are no collections or folders allowed at this time. There's a "light sensor" in the upper lefthand corner (in portrait mode) but there's no setting for using auto-brightness, so what this sensor is used for is beyond me.The Kindle Fire is, of course, even more useful for people heavily into the Amazon ecosystem. Our household has used Amazon as our primary source of electronics, household items, etc. for a long time. We already own a Kindle (keyboard) as well. This makes it a logical choice over the offering BN is coming out with (the Nook Tablet) despite the lesser system specs of the Fire. For others who don't mind dropping an extra $50 and who aren't "hooked on Amazon" like we are, it may drive a purchase decision the other way, but this does not make the Fire a poor product, period.If Amazon continues to improve the Fire's software, their curation of Fire apps, and continue adding value in terms of Prime benefits, the Fire will grow to be a true 5-star item. The wide variety of reviews for the Fire right now is due to some people reviewing for potential, some people reviewing (like I am) for current ability, and some people reviewing for unrealistic expectations. Again, don't expect $500+ worth of hardware for $200 and you'll be much, much happier in the end. (We have two Fires for less than one iPad, making us twice as happy, for 25% less . . . ;)(P.S. If you ever think your accelerometer is broken, make sure you haven't "locked" your Fire in the settings bar. One of the Fires got "stuck" in vertical mode for a while and it took some fiddling to figure that little detail out!)Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

