fi is a netgear wndr 3700 router my husband bought back in 2010 and is connected to a Motorola 6120b docsis 3.0 modem getting ( per speedtest.net) 30 mbps download and more than 4 mbps upload here in jackson mississippi.  Also I'm less than 10 feet away from the router while it's on the floor basically nothing blocking it's line of sight. Thus your results may vary depending your internet distribution devices, your isp, and many other things.Flash that works as it should for websites and other content that requires it to fully load/work/show up: Check. ( although I have yet to encounter anything that requires it that I need when doing a Kindle Fire : husband's win 7 pro 64 bit gaming machine's website test on more than 30 different flash including websites.)Great battery life: Check( I read the reviews and specs of the Fire claiming it has up to 8 hours of reading, I set the brightness to 70%, sound completely to 0, turned off Wifi, version 6.3 updated already, and I literally got 7 hours 45 minutes on the dot from a 100% battery until that last minute the device auto shut down. Good enough for me.  I read alot but never more than 4 hours straight without a break anyways.)Only speed bump in my experience with the Fire so far was getting it updated to 6.3 from 6.2.  I did not know I must purchase a micro usb data/sync charge cable, download the update from another computer, connect the cable to the Fire ( the rest is in the instructions on amazon.com's website. Easy to find) However, I figured out a fairy easy ( although tedious for me) way.On the other computer you're using for reference, right click ( if in windows.  or secondary click if on a mac) the link of the update that you normally click to download for the Fire.  copy the exact url into your web address bar at the top..  don't go there just paste it in there.Now, on your kindle pull up whatever webpage you want ( my case. google.com) in your address bar at the top type in the EXACT url you have in the address bar on your Reference computer.  You will then automatically start downloading the update.Here's the exact url link as I found it.[...]**Very important**Not sure if this matters.. The INSTALLATION process for the update did NOT begin UNTIL the battery reached at least 40/41 percent battery charge level ( was in the middle of charging the Fire with the including ac wall adapter)  Thus I believe the battery level must be at that as a minimum.Also the installation process did not begin until I rebooted the Fire but pressing ( not holding more than a second if that)  Just food for thought in case anyone didn't feel like spending more money on a cable just to update the device. I ordered one anyways ( the $5.45 one) so that I can easily plug in the Fire to hubby's pc to transfer any media I need.Yes I know.  TEDIOUS, but still it worked for me.  No headaches or hassles other than that.This device ( In my opinion) doesn't lag but rarely and it's never more than once.  You're not paying top dollar for hardcore hardware under the hood.  If you want a guaranteed lag free touch screen experience on any tablet ( bigger than 7 inches) get the 3rd gen or the " New iPad" and spend that extra 300 bucks if you want.Fire has all the tweaking settings I need.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (2)

