6 of 7 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsNot perfect, but close to it,March 29, 2012By&nbsp;Jeremy Morgan "A good book on your shelf is a...(Gaston, Oregon)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Ok, so I've used my Kindle fire enough to give it a review, I really wanted to break this thing in before doing so. I'll post all the stuff I would want to know before buying it. I've beaten this thing up and used the heck out of it and now it's time to review itNote: I make comparisons to the 2nd generation Kindle Keyboard because that's what I had before. There are a few differences you should know before ditching that old kindle.The Good:There is tons of stuff to do on this thing. You can read a book, magazine, news, watch a movie, play a game, whatever. It's a quantum leap from the old Kindle where you could read and play some very limited games. This thing is a boredom killer.The colors and graphics are fantastic. It simply looks great and there isn't much more to say about that.Netflix and Hulu stream PERFECTLY on this device. You'll only be limited by your internet connection. It delivers crisp, high definition video smooth as silk. I was amazed at what video looks like on this thing.Type is easy to read on this device. You can switch from black on white, to black on sepia or white on black depending on preference. The type is clear, legible and you can adjust size and spacing easily. My longest time reading so far is about 3 hours, no eye strain, no headaches.The sensitivity and accuracy of the touch screen are top notch. I've been using a lot of tablets and touch screen phones lately and this is among the top for sure in that category. It's extremely sensitive to taps and touch so you won't get frustrated using this. I intentionally let the screen get a lot of smudges on it to see how it affected it, and it did fine. It's at the level of an iPad in this department (if you've ever used one) and light years ahead of these cheap tablets on the market. Angry birds is a breeze and you won't have to tap multiple times to get it to listen to you.Battery life is pretty good considering what it does. It's nowhere near my 2nd gen kindle but that's to be expected now that we have a bright screen and way more features. It's enough that you can use it to watch a movie or read for a few hours and be ok.PDFs seem to look pretty good on it. I transferred some to my old Kindle and could barely read them, but with the fire they are very close to a Kindle book, legible and look great.Fast response - I haven't had any problems with response time at all. Everything flows very smooth and quick.Feels tough - My last Kindle died young, and I know it was party because of how I treated it. I used it daily and carried it everywhere. This one feels a lot more sturdy and I think it will hold up much better than the last one. It's a tough thing to describe but it just feels more sturdy.Space - They give you ample room to put your books and other media on this device. It's nice to not have to worry about space for objects.Keyboard - This ties in with the touchscreen part but it works very well. You can type up twitter/facebook posts with ease, and works good even if you have big fingers like me.Fun - this thing is just fun to use, and has so many features.Quality - I'll reiterate this point - it feels very sturdy, performs well and is easy to use. I can really see the effort and amount of care that was put into making a great product here. It is far beyond what you'd expect for $200.The Bad:Well there isn't much!The lack of 3g - I understand why they did it: obviously streaming movies, tv shows, games etc over 3G would be very cost prohibitive for Amazon. I get that. But it is something that you miss if you had it before.The fact that most of the books live in the cloud until you download them - This was kind of annoying and ties into the 3g part, when I first got this, i opened up one book and looked at it, and the next day went to work (where we have no wi-fi) and it was nearly useless. All of the books had to be downloaded (which I eventually did) before they could be read when you're away from a wireless connection. Kinda crappy.Lack of folder support - I transferred many of my books from my old Kindle to the new one because they were separated by folders. The Kindle itself didn't recognize these folders, but when using USB transfers it was easier to organize everything - fine on my 2nd gen kindle - but with the fire if it's in a folder it won't find it. So I have to dump all my books into the root directory and it's a huge clustered mess. They all show up on the carousel the same but I liked having folders to organize stuff.Speaking of carousel, the last stuff you used being popped up on there all the time can get annoying, especially when you delete it and it comes back later. A very small thing to get upset about, but it's there.Sound kind of sucks - Not the greatest, but when you consider the size of the device they're doing the best they can. Headphones work great.Too much distractions - If you want to read, it might be hard not to play angry birds, read some news or watch Netflix. If you just simply want to read books a 1st or 2nd gen kindle is fine, but if you want a bunch of other distractions in there too, the Fire has it.The Final Word:GET IT. There is no really compelling reason not to get this if you can afford it. I have tested and tried several tablets for work and spent a lot of time with them and if you consider the Kindle fire "just another tablet" it's still the best in the $200 market, by far. If you think about it as a Kindle it's leaps and bounds ahead of the 2nd gen which is only $60 less. Why on earth wouldn't you get it?It's very well done, a high quality product worth getting. It's how things should be made.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (2)

