6 of 7 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsIt's Good!,December 30, 2011By&nbsp;Aaron Tensen(Oregon)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I received my Kindle Fire on Christmas so I have had it for about a week now, but have used it for countless hours in that short amount of time. It works pretty perfectly for my needs, as I have already purchased many TV shows, books, and have uploaded most of my music to Amazon's cloud. Having all of my content ready from the get-go was a definite plus as I was able to start consuming content immediately after opening the box without waiting for hours while my music or movies downloaded on the device. Of course if I'm on the go I will need to make sure I have some content on the device, but that seems to be a breeze and a computer is not needed to do so.Web surfing seems to be as good as one would expect on a 7inch screen. It's decently fast and gets the job done, but convenience is really the Fire's strong suit as I no longer have to lug around my hot and heavy laptop to visit my favorite web pages. My laptop is now hooked straight up to the TV for watching videos on the big screen and is controlled via All In One app from the appstore, so it's a win-win for me.The screen looks great on the Fire and makes playing games or watching videos a joy. Plants vs. Zombies is what my girlfriend and I have mostly been playing, but the free app of the day from the app store has added several other great games to my library. I can't really say how reading is on the Fire as I have a 2nd gen Kindle that I still prefer to use while reading, but the screen is certainly sharp enough to read in comfort.As far as the battery goes, I have to say that I was impressed with the life it has especially with the screen being so vibrant. I haven't timed how long it lasts, but I can use the Fire for a good chunk of the day without worrying about the battery. This makes using the device a real treat for me because my laptop has a bad battery and only lasts for a few minutes, so my prior mobility was limited and I'm happy to no longer be tethered to the wall.It's easy to go on and on about what I love about the Fire, but I do have a few problems with it. First of all, it sometimes fails to detect my headphones when they are plugged into the jack and just plays audio through the main speakers instead, which is a real drag. Restarting the Kindle fixed this problem both times it has happend, but who wants to do that every time headphones are needed? Certainly not me. Secondly, since there are no external buttons, (Home, volume) adjusting the volume or going to the home screen can take a bit of time getting used to. Once I learned how to adjust the volume from any screen it's not really that big of a deal for me. My biggest problem with the no external buttons is when I have the keyboard up while browsing, there is no easy access to the home screen, or back buttons which can be frustrating. There needs to be a button to bring the keyboard back down, and perhaps there is but I'm just missing it.  Another problem I have is when I open the browser it automatically opens a web page that I looked at long ago. I tried deleting my history, or looking for some sort of homepage option that it may have been set to, but so far no luck. All of these problems are minor and seem to be ones that could be fixed in a future update.All in all, the Kindle Fire is a great device for my needs and comes at a great price. If you are looking for something to do some web browsing, play some games, and watch some videos then this is the device to get, especially if you have already invested in Amazon's content library.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

