6 of 7 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsPerfect for what it's intended to be,December 13, 2011By&nbsp;Donald Gillette(Nashville)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I've read quite a few reviews about the Kindle Fire and all "its problems" but so far after using it daily for a month, I've seen no problem at all.I'll take what it does one thing at a time, but honestly, the only thing it's not great at is browing the web and that's just because it's a mobile device--they all suck at browsing the web, even the venerable iPad.E-reader: I prefer it to my Kindle 1 because the print is sharper and I can read it in the dark.  Swiping the screen to turn the page may seem inconvenient to some, but it's no more inconvenient than clicking the button on the other Kindles and it beats hell out of the terribly difficult task of turning a page in a real book. That was sarcasm. It's missing the text-to-speech feature of the other Kindles so far but rumor is that'll be available in the next update. I personally hate "listening" to books but some people love it.  If you've gotta have that feature, you might wait for the update and see if the feature's in there.Videos: Great for Netflix, Hulu, Amazon video, and DVDs that have been converted to MP4.  It plays MP4's, not avi files or mpegs. The built-in speakers are just "okay" but with headphones, the sound is no different than an iPod.Email: Perfect little machine for reading emails.  No better or worse at writing them than an android phone, an iPhone, or anything else with the keyboard on screen.Apps:  Every app I've tried works great including the all-important Angry Birds. Some apps aren't available through the Amazon app store and that's where you're forced to go when you try to download any app.  HBO GO, for example, is not available yet for Kindle Fire even though it works like a dream on an Android phone.  I assume Amazon's playing catch-up with this. Or at least I hope so.Web browsing:  Not great. Better than an Android phone or Blackberry, not as good as a desktop. It works for a quick google search but you wouldn't want to spend all day on it because it's a pain just like all tablets. In my opinion, without a mouse or a keyboard, web browsing isn't worth the time--even on a netbook with a mousepad, it's no treat.Photo viewing:  Very cool.  Sharp, clear, and zoomable.Music: Also great, just like a big iPod, but really--you don't buy a Kindle Fire to listen to music.Shopping on Amazon:  Way too easy. You have to watch yourself or you'll be buying the kitchen sinkWhat you're getting with a Kindle Fire is an Android phone with a big screen and a lot longer battery life but without a camera, microphone, or telephone.  There are a lot of things they could have included but then the price would be through the roof.  I bought this because it was $199 vs. the iPad's $499 and to me, that's a huge difference. It could use a USB port, an exterior volume control, and text-to-speech.Some of the critics are slamming it because of an unresponsive screen, claiming that anybody with big hands can't use it and that's baloney. My big Irish mitts are the size of boxing gloves, and I've had absolutely no problem. You have to ~learn~ how to use it and that takes a day or two. Just grabbing it and dragging a ham across the screen isn't going to work. You didn't get behind the wheel of your first car and win the Daytona 500, so don't expect to become a Kindle Fire wizard right out of the box, but just a little practice and use and you'll love the thing. Seriously, every negative review I've read on the Kindle Fire has "impatient moron" written all over it.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

