6 of 7 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsExcellent for the price!,December 21, 2011By&nbsp;P. Swain "Parabolee"(NJ, USA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Let's be clear from the start, I am giving the Kindle Fire 5 stars because of it's price. There is simply no other Tablet on the market as good as the Kindle Fire in this price range. Also let me note that I am an iPad 2 owner reviewing this product I bought as a gift. So I have no bias towards the device as an owner of one. As I am not.Let's start with the devices positives.+ The device has a wonderful UI that is nicer than most Android UI's. The dual-core processor is fast and the device is easy and fun to use. If you are in the market for an inexpensive tablet, you really can't do better than the Kindle Fire.+ Also since it's from Kindle you know it will continue to be well supported with updates and improved features over time.+ The browser is very nice and it handles emails very well. I also tested it with several 3D games and it ran than great.+ The screen is gorgeous and a high resolution. Higher than the iPad (although half the size). After looking at this for a while the iPad screen looks very low resolution.+ Anything you buy from Amazon is stored for free in the cloud to save your storage.Now the downsides. You get what you pay for as the old adage goes. But we are only talk a lack of features that many would not want/need, rather than a lack of quality.- No Android marketplace. The Amazon app store is great, but limited in choices in comparison to the Android Marketplace. And while you can "side-load" apps that are not on the Amazon app store, many will not know how to do that so you app choices have limitations. The Android marketplace can be installed if you have some hacking knowhow or are good at following guides, but it's a pain and currently will be disabled whenever Amazon send out an update (although it can be reinstalled).- No bluetooth. Few will care, but this means no Bluetooth keyboard or gaming accessories (see OnLive's bluetooth controller)- No external storage options. This also applies to the iPad but many Android devices allow the use of SD card to increase storage.- No 3G option for those wanting internet access on the go. You pay an extra $100 for this on the ipad but it would be nice if Amazon offered a more expensive model with this feature.- No volume buttons, volume accessed via on screen menu only. Pretty minor this as it only takes a few seconds to pull the menu up onscreen. But buttons would have been nice.As I said there are better tablets on the market. But none of them are close to this price range. If you want something better than the Fire you really need to spend $500, so the price difference is huge.GREAT TABLET. LOVE IT!Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

