6 of 7 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsGreat little device,December 14, 2011By&nbsp;Gadgeteer-See all my reviewsThis review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I was recently given a Kindle Fire as an early Christmas gift and could not wait to take it out of the box, if only to see for myself if the controversy about it is correct. I will say upfront that I live in both the Apple ecosystem and the Amazon Prime ecosystem. I own Macs, iPods, iPhones, and an iPad. With two adults and three children in our home, we considered adding another iPad, as our gadgets are in constant use. After using the Fire, however, I can safely say I will postpone that purchase if not cancel it altogether.I find the interconnectedness with Amazon Prime to be fantastic. I was able to immediately stream a free movie with zero buffering time and no jerky video that one often gets when viewing video over a Wi-Fi connection. As with all the Kindles, downloading a book is a breeze. I have also used it to mindlessly browse the web while watching TV. That experience was satisfactory, if a little kludgy, but I expect the forthcoming software update to address any issues with the Silk web-browser.While the touch interface is not quite as graceful as the iPad, i find it to be very intuitive and easy to use. Many of the negative reviews have focused on the "Carousel" feature (this is like cover flow on an iPod, except you can leaf through every activity you have used). Currently, it cannot be edited, so your history is there for all to see. I would like to see this feature be editable, but again, I am pretty sure Amazon has heard this complaint and will allow this in the software update. Its not that anyone is trying to hide anything, but if you navigated to a useless webpage after a search, this would remain in the Carousel. So it is more of an annoyance than anything. Many of the features, like its e-mail aggregator, work as easily as the iPad, although using Exchange e-mail supposedly requires a separate app. Overall, however, the user experience is well above average.In the first three days I've had the Fire, I've read a book, watched a movie, used it to conduct web searches (and watched Flash video), answered e-mail, played games. I'm like a kid in a candy store with my very portable little tablet.I rarely write reviews, but given all the controversy and bad publicity the Fire has gotten I felt compelled to set the record straight. The Fire would be a great tablet at a higher price point as well, but for $200 it is a steal, especially if you already use Amazon prime. While I love my Apple products too, I've loved my Fire. I can't wait to get home at night to play with it some more. I'm pretty sure the naysayers own a large position in Apple stock.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

