6 of 7 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsGood economical reader and mostly Android tablet.,December 7, 2011By&nbsp;Brian Trotter-See all my reviewsThis review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)To be clear, this is not an "Ipad Killer".  If you want every feature of an Ipad, then pay four times as much and get one.  However, if you want a solid reader, a decent web browser, and a decent selection of Amazon's Android apps, this is a very good bargain.Out of the box, you'll get a system update, but that's par for the course with lots of consumer electronics.  Apps are available from Amazon's app store.  You will be locked out of the standard Android app store, but in general the items in the Amazon Store are certified to work with the Fire's features.There is no camera.  This wasn't an issue to me, I have plenty of cameras.  It does have a decently responsive touch screen, and I was able to use it to draw a decent resolution drawing with a $1.99 app in the app store.The web browser is NOT as fast as Amazon claims it is... which I think is in part that they miscalculated the effect of server load on their cloud web server.  If their claims about cloud serving are true then as Amazon scales up its servers you should see better performance.  So far, I haven't found any website that was inaccessible or unreadable.  Overall, the browser performs well.The keyboard is tricky for folks like me with big ham hands.. in portrait mode, I tend to hit the wrong buttons a lot... If you get a stylus designed to work with the Ipad and IPod, you'll find it works very well on the Fire.The acellerometer works quite well, allowing you to play games that run by tilting.There are two issues I've had.  The first is that the power button is literally right next to the usb port. If you're not careful, every time you unplug the fire, you'll turn it off by bumping the switch...The second issue, and this is actually a big one for me, is that Google's platform functions are locked out.  This means android programs that are designed to sync with Google Calendar or use Google Apps functionality simply will not work as intended.  As such, those apps generally don't even find their way to the Amazon app store... an notable exception is Pocket Informant which syncs with Google Calendar on every other android device, but cannot on the Kindle Fire.  Ironic that on 12/7/2011, it was Amazon's Free App of the day...  The apparant reason behind the Google Mobile Services lockout is to force app designers into the Amazon Web Services.  This is an issue I hope Amazon changes their position on for future updates.Overall, if you're looking for a good economical tablet to read, play games, and surf, this is a good bargain and quite probably your best bang for the buck.  You can compare it to the Ipad 2 if you want... but prepare to factor in the 3 times higher price while you make the comparison.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

