6 of 7 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsJust what I wanted,November 30, 2011By&nbsp;B. Dunn(USA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)In short:  Kindle Fire is great for email, streaming, internet, books, and it is offered at a fair price.  Bad because of some concerns with the way Amazon ships, and not sure if putting the power button on the bottom is so smart.  See below:First, before you receive your Kindle, you need to take steps to protect yourself.  If you purchase for yourself, Amazon will automatically link the Kindle to your account.  What this means is that someone can intercept your shipment, and can use your new kindle to make purchases under your account.  ALL WITHOUT LOGGING IN.  What I recommend is when purchasing you select "this is a gift", so Amazon won't automatically link your device to your account.  If you have already purchased the kindle, and are still waiting for it to arrive... IMMEDIATELY log into your account and deactivate your device.  You can reactivate it once it is in your hands.  This way if someone steals your package, it is only the device and not your wallet.  Amazon doesn't require a signature, so UPS will leave it on your doorstep!Second, many people have complained that there is no lock feature for the device.  There is, you just need to go into the set up and activate the lock feature.  It is there..you just need to set it up.  I recommend that you use this feature because once you activate your kindle... as I said above, it is linked to your account.Some of the navigation in the books is a little difficult.  One tip I can tell you is that if you are reading a book, and you want to back out... you need to tap the screen to get the icon to return to the home page.  It would be nice if Amazon included an update that has a "pop up" telling people that.Overall, I am very impressed with the Kindle Fire.  The screen looks amazing, and it seems to work very well.  I have used it to download books, email, internet, and stream videos on Amazon and Netflix.  Netflix seemed a little pixilated, while Amazon seemed clear.  But I noticed no jerking or slowing of the streamed content.  I am running on 10M on my internet download speeds.I have downloaded one magazine thus far, and it seems acceptable.  It is not one that contains the interactive material, so it is just the basic magazine.  I have downloaded several books, and the text looks great on the screen and the controls to change the text and lighting are easy enough to change.  I know some people have complained about the brightness, but I don't think they are aware that you can change this.So, if you want a smaller device than the iPad, something that gives you email, internet, streaming, reading, and simple gaming materials, then I would recommend the Kindle Fire.  If you want the larger screen, then the iPad would be more for you, but if you go that big, why not just get yourself a laptop?  The Kindle Fire won't fit into your pocket like a cell phone, so purchase yourself a case... I'm still waiting on mine for some reason.The power button on the bottom is a bit of a pain, but so far for most of my apps, it hasn't been a major issue.  I just turn the screen so that the power button is on top.  Only some games and apps seem to have a problem with this, but the things you would use most like email, video, and internet seem unaffected.I would and have recommended the Kindle Fire to my friends.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

