3 of 3 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsJust what we needed for the price we could afford.,April 4, 2012By&nbsp;SoCal Boy "SCB"(California)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Main motivator for getting the Kindle Fire is to keep our our 18 month old occupied on an overseas flight to England from Los Angeles. We've been playing around with it for a few days and it's amazing. We're Apple heavy, with Macbook Pros and iPhone 4S's and we are definitely looking to an iPad once we can afford it, for the functionality that it offers.  But for the price of the Kindle, it's definitely the best tablet alternative to the iPad, if you're not looking for the specifically Apple extensions and apps.  I read the reviews about how it's limited... haven't run into a wall yet.There's also a kid app, that locks the main functions of the tablet away from your kids. You can use it as a gateway for other Apps such as Netflix, Fruit Ninja, etc. and once you try to exit out of it, it just goes back to the App's main menu. Perfect for any button mashing, touchscreen swiping 18 month old who has deleted applications, called 911 on Emergency Call mode, and discovered laptop and phone functions their parents can't get out of. You have to verify you're an adult to exit the program by either verifying your age or drawing a letter "Z".We got a refurbished unit which was on sale, one of my main concerns was battery life. No hold backs there. Charged it once and it's been running for 3 days (useage of about 2 to 3 hours each day) with about 60% of battery life left.  Just downloaded our son's favorite movies and video clips to it. I think it's going to keep him occupied all the way to England and back just fine.My recommendation, if you're comparing between the iPad and the Kindle and you're on a limited budget. If you can't think of something that is specifically iPad exclusive. Get the Kindle. My personal example of an iPad only application that I would have is using the DJay application with a DJ controller. But I already have that combination on the Macbook Pro with a backup on the iPhone. For those of you who don't even have an Apple product, you won't miss anything by going with the Kindle. In fact you'll have $300+ more dollars in your pocket to buy music, movies, apps and accessories with.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (3)

