3 of 3 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsReally Nice Device But It's Amazon's Service That Clinches It,February 20, 2012By&nbsp;J. Windham "Book and Movie Lover"(Grand Cane, La USA)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Critical Review of Nook vs. KindleI own the Nook eReader and I own a Kindle Fire, and while I know these two devices aren't quite on par (one being an eReader, one being a color tablet), owning both has allowed me to interact with both Barnes and Noble and Amazon and this review is more a critique of the companies' services than the devices themselves.Let me say first of all, that I love both my devices, the Nook and the Fire.  I use them often and have recommended them to others.  All things being equal, I've yet to find a great deal of difference between B&N;'s devices and Amazon's devices.  Their eReaders are very similar, their color tablets are also very similar in design and functionality.  A friend of mine has the Nook Tablet, so I was able to compare this to the Fire.  There might be some slight differences (and I'm sure other reviewers have gone into the nitty gritty of what differences exist), but they are so similar I think either device would please its owner.The true difference lies, for me, with the companies themselves: the level of customer service, the amount of eBooks available, the price of books and apps.  And in this aspect I think that Amazon wins.Here is a list of some of the critical points I have noticed where B&N; falls short of Amazon:* On more than one occasion, Barnes and Noble has not had a book available in eBook format for its Nook, yet I can go onto Amazon and find that same book available for the Kindle.  I don't know exactly how the contracting with the book publishers works -but it seems that if Amazon had it in Kindle format, than B&N; should also have it available for the Nook.* Amazon makes it very easy to find free eBook selections.  Barnes and Nobles tends to bury to free selections, making you search thru their higher prices versions and the .99 cent versions.  You can often use the trick by typing 0.00 after the book title to see if a free version is available.  Amazon usually lists the free selections first, making it very easy to find.* Barnes and Nobles has an extensive list of Classics that it offers in eBook format - Jane Eyre, Treasure Island, Little Women, etc.  Only about five of these are available for free, the rest are priced at $3.99.  Amazon has every single "classic" available for free.  Since these books are beyond their copyright expiration date, there is no reason why they shouldn't be offered for free.* Barnes and Noble does have a selling point in that they can offer in-store, in-person customer service.  If you have a question or problem with your Nook, you can walk into the nearest B&N; and get some help.  When you are purchasing your device, it's also nice to be able to go in and actually try one out - something that you obviously cannot do with Amazon.  This is a big selling point.  When I buy devices like the eReader, I like to be able to actually see and touch what I'm getting before I buy it.  Ironically, however, this same advantage also brought a problem to my attention.  I was in our local B&N; perusing the Sale Book section when I spotted a book I wanted.  I took out my Nook, logged into B&N;'s wireless and brought up the book in their Nook store.  Under Nook, it was full price - almost $15.00 more than the in store sale price.  If B&N; puts their in-store books on sale, then they ought to make their Nook books match the sale price.  I have never searched a book on Amazon where the Kindle price and the paperback price didn't match.* Barnes and Nobles should consider implementing a loyalty program like Amazon's "Prime Membership".  I am a member of Prime and the perks are completely worth the yearly fee.  You get free shipping on items, you get reduced prices on eBooks, movies, apps.  Often, under Prime Membership, you can get normally priced eBooks for free.  Barnes and Noble does have a yearly membership that gives you in-store discounts....but as far as I can see, they have not extended this to include eBooks.Now, some might read the above list and think that I am completely anti-Barnes and Noble and this is not the case at all.  As I stated earlier, I love my Nook eReader and for all of B&N; shortfalls, I wouldn't trade it for the world.  This list does highlight, however,  several things B&N; could do to improve and if they want to continue to compete in the cut throat world of eReaders and iPads , I think many of these things must be addressed in the futureHelp other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment (1)

