3 of 3 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsKindle + Tablet = Success,January 23, 2012By&nbsp;Sizzle-See all my reviewsThis review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Going into this purchase, I was already the proud owner of a Kindle 4 and an iPad. I never really use my iPad, and I was wishing the Kindle could do just a little more, to save me from pulling out my laptop when I'm away from the house. So, I was looking into some options, and it came down to upgrading to an iPad 2, and installing the Kindle App, or picking up a Kindle Fire. In the end, I picked up a Kindle Fire, and I don't regret it.First, picking up an iPad 2 would not only have cost more than twice as much, but it would have felt foolish with the next generation coming to stores so soon. The price of the Kindle Fire is definitely appropriate for everything it can do. It's basically a small Android tablet, backed up by Amazon, and its Kindle powerhouse. Sure, it's a little more sluggish than the iPad in loading up webpages, and the user experience could use a few tweaks, but there really isn't anything that gets anywhere close to pushing me away.Since the purchase, I've thrown a screen protector and Seidio Active case (with a hard screen cover and stand) on this little thing, and I throw it in my bag every morning before I head out to class. When I need to check a little something online that goes beyond my iPhone comfort (PDF file or the like), I don't need to pull out a laptop. That's not only less time-consuming, but it's less revealing in some situations (think, showing a bunch of strangers that you have a MacBook Air in that backpack). Even better, I don't have to completely stop walking to check these things (but that doesn't mean I'll be tumbling into any fountains, or at least not on camera).It's also great as a tablet for watching TV. It gives me enough internet access and other functionality to, once again, keep me from reaching for a computer, and it's small enough that it really sits on the couch easily, and it seems solid enough to handle the possibility of someone bumping it.So, for a couple hundred bucks, Amazon hooks it up with a great little tablet. Sure, it could use a few upgrades to bring it anywhere close to the iPad, but it's a great entry-level tablet, with dimensions some might find more comfortable, and it's also a Kindle with a turbo kit. I'd give it five stars if they worked on some simple user experience issues. I really want to give it 4.5 stars, but that's not an option.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

3 of 3 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsbest value,January 23, 2012By&nbsp;capsfan88-See all my reviewsThis review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)After days of scanning online reviews, careful research, and trying out several tablets, I decided to buy the Kindle Fire.I must say that I am very happy with my purchase. The device is perfect for what I need: E-mail, books, and occasional movies and tv shows.Strengths:- Size: While the small screen isn't the greatest for magazines or Pdf's, its actually great for ebooks, and it feels  much better in your hand. Other larger devices (ie Ipad2) feel awkward and cumbersome after a while for reading over longer periods.-Amazon Prime: In order to get the most out of this device, you need Amazon prime, the service which lets you borrow 1 book a month from the Amazon kindle library, gives you access to certain shows and movies (the selection is comparable/slightly inferior to Netflix at the moment, but will presummably be beefed up in the coming year), and offers free two day shipping on all Amazon products.-Video/quality: Overall selection and feel of apps, and the quality of video were a positive surprise for a $200 device.Weaknesses:- Sound: The volume doesn't go high enough. Period. The quality also leaves something to be desired.- Power Button: Much has been made about this in online reviews. The location, while dumb, isn't the end of the world. I have hit it by accident a few times, but there's an easy fix: Rotate the device so that the button is on top. Problem solved.-Storage: simply not enough if you want to have a lot of music and movies.My advice to those looking into getting a tablet is know what you want to use the device for. Originally I had planned to use the device for a bit of business + Books and a few apps and occasional movies. I realized that even the Ipad2 isn't very useful for business (taking notes that sort of thing). Thus i settled on the fire, primarily for its price, functionality (gives you everything the high end tablets give you without the bells and whistles).For those who watch a lot of video and listen to music, this may not be the device to you. If a few movies on the device is all you need, and you otherwise focus on ebooks, apps, e-mail and web this is the device for you.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

