3 of 3 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsnorjon_36054,January 14, 2012By&nbsp;John E. Norris-See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I already had a Kindle e-reader (the kind with buttons) and I often wished it connected to the web.  I tried connecting under "experimental" and it connected, but was practically unusable.  When the Fire came out, I had to have one.  I have not regretted it.  If you have not had an Android device, there is a learning curve to figure out what the control icons mean, but then it's just a matter of swearing at it a sufficient amount of times until it becomes OK, just like all electronic devices.  I already had an Amazon Prime membership, which I bought when it meant nothing but fast and free shipping.  Then Amazon threw in streaming movies and 5G of cloud drive at no extra cost. The Fire has proved to be an excellent companion.  It plays music (my music or web music) for me while I read my favorite recently downloaded ebook (speakers are better than I expected - headphones are better than that), lets me check my email between chapters, acts as a flashlight (app for that) when I want to go to bed without waking my wife, and lets me surf the web or check the weather or Facebook without the hassle of firing up my laptop or desktop.  I do read quite a bit on it, and it's just the  right size for that.  It didn't come with a mini USB cable, which is necessary to access the Fire's storage by computer, but I found that the one I use to charge my cell phone works just fine. I tried Netflix and Amazon Prime movies, and it works great at home, but not in a hotel room (not enough available bandwidth at the hotel, I guess).  I have a couple of games, but playing games is not my thing, so they don't get used much. I loaded the pictures from our recent trip to Grand Canyon on the Fire from my computer, which the Fire could display one by one or in a slide show(holder's choice), using the included Gallery app .  I like  that I can start my music collection and it will play until the battery runs down, so I can take the music from room to room to keep me company without it shutting off. If you read much news, there is a USA Today app that works beautifully on the Fire. The Fire really is an entertainment device.  You can go from entertaining thing to entertaining thing very easily and often at the same time, and the 7" size makes it easier to read than a smart phone or Ipod and more portable than a larger tablet.  It's the right size for me.  By the way, the Fire has a free Pandora app and I like the "Yoga" station for reading background music (if you like New Age).One thing that does annoy me a lot is that I can't more easily get to the volume control when I'm playing music on the speakers while doing something else. It complicates things if I want to stop the music when the phone rings. The screen on the Fire goes blank after a while, but the music will still play (I have it set up that way).  To get back in and turn the volume down, I have to reopen the Fire, which is not that simple since I have it password protected. Also, once I get to the volume slider, it is not always immediately responsive.  There must be a better way.  So far the 8G of storage area has not been a problem, but I can see it becoming a problem in the future, if I want to begin loading more of my stuff on it.that being said, I'm really pleased with the Fire.  If it got broken, stolen, lost, etc., I would buy another one.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment (1)

