3 of 3 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsHave had my Fire for a month now,December 15, 2011By&nbsp;Hoosiermama "Mary Loveless"(Indianapolis, In USA)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)I've had my Fire for about a month now, and find that I love it! I had a K2, which I recently upgraded to a Touch (gave the K2 to my son), so I do the majority of my reading on the Touch. I do some reading on the Fire, though, and it's especially nice when reading before bed, because I don't need a light on the Fire. I absolutely LOVE the Prime movies, and have watched three of them, that I had been wanting to see. The video quality is excellent, and streams nicely. We have a SLOW DSL line (considered high speed, but it's the lowest speed that's considered high speed, and all that's available to us), and movies stream without any pauses, even when I watch in the other end of the house from our wireless modem.It has a good variety of apps from the Amazon store, but I do wish I could access the Amazon Market without rooting (I have no intention of rooting and losing the Prime movies). I can sideload apps from GetJar, though, and that has worked well. I'm one that likes Amazon's interface, but I do look forward to being able to edit what's in the carousel. I've always stored my music in Amazon's cloud, so my music is there and ready for me.I didn't buy this device in place of an Ipad. I bought it for what Amazon offers, knowing that it's limited by wifi and storage content. I am usually in a wifi area (home or work), but did take it with us on a vacation last week. It worked flawlessly, connecting easily to wifi networks in three different hotels. Much, much easier to travel with than a laptop. I haven't had issues with the on/off button that others have complained about. Storage hasn't been an issue for me. I have one movie on it, and multiple apps, and still have almost 5 gigs of storage left, so at least for now, storage isn't an issue for me.To be honest, I had never had an interest in an Ipad or other tablet. I have a smartphone and a laptop, and really didn't see the value in spending $500 for a tablet. With the Fire, I have a $200 tablet that does what I want it to do. It's more of a play device, and I use the desktop and/or laptop for more serious things. The Fire has been much more than I expected. When I bought it and the Touch at the same time, I wasn't sure if I'd keep either of them, but I was curious about them. I not only kept the Fire, but have ordered another as a Christmas gift.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

