3 of 3 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsGreat little entertainment device, some flaws,November 17, 2011By&nbsp;JonathanJW-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)As an iPad owner/user, I had realistic expectations and needs for this device.  I intended for this to be a secondary device for entertainment at home (reading/movies/games/net surfing). As a parent, a tablet gives you flexibility to watch your kids while still having a variety of entertainment options on hand no matter where you are at home.  I have found that the iPad is a very popular device and often more than one person would like to use it.The Great:  Price, look and feel - For a second device this price point is spot-on and the device feels good to hold and use (mostly).The Good:  easy to use, very portable - The interface is logical, if not intuitive.  I would rate this higher but the carousel remembering everything recent rather than being a favorites bar is a mistake.  Plus, I would love to be able to sort my books in collections.The Bad:  WiFi seems a bit weak, I had to be standing within 20 feet of my router to get full signal (I can sit 80 ft away in my driveway and have full strength on my iPad). Sound control is awkward, having no external buttons for sound means having to drill into settings for many tasks.  e.g. The sound control is built into the Prime video streaming and lets you adjust on the fly, but Netflix has no sound controls, so you have to open settings - the movie pauses - adjust and go back.  Also, the little gray bar that appears at the bottom of some apps needs to be tweaked, I would eliminate the white color of the arrow and make it a darker gray so it is less obvious (I really noticed it using Netflix).The Awful:  The power button is a disaster.  The location itself is bad enough as it is right at a place where you might hold the device if you are using one hand (like when you are reading)so I found I was constantly shutting it off when I moved my hands.  Worse yet is that the button takes very little pressure to activate so it just exacerbates the location problem.  I would suggest they design a cap of some sort that could clip on to cover it while in use.Overall, I am extremely satisfied (I gave it 4 stars, but really give it 3.5).  Setup was easy and it came ready to go out of the box.  I found that, as others have pointed out the device occasionally stutters, as you will touch an input and it won't seem to respond, then it will suddenly go on.  The device is solid and heavy which while it gives a feel of quality, though it is a little heavy when compared to reading a paperback or other kindle device.  I enjoyed reading on it and watching video was pleasant as well; both Amazon and Netflix pictures were good and the size of the video wasn't much smaller than an iPad due to the letterbox format. If I didn't own an iPad I would have no comparison for this and could see this working very well as a Primary tablet for a home user.  I have trouble envisioning this being great on the road due to the limited storage space and reliance on WiFi.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comments (2)

