t takes getting used to for me, since I cannot even stand a Blackberry!  I love my Kindle3, so I also got a Kindle Touch to replace that one with, since reading on a back-lit device is hard for my eyes and I knew that going into it.  I bought the Kindle Fire for other uses, such as being able to be on top of my business e-mail while on the road, without needing to pay a monthly fee or getting a phone that takes me ten minutes to get into.  Oh, I can wait to find a hot spot, no issues there.  I see the Kindle Fire as an addition to my life, not the other way around.  If you don't like needing to use WiFi to access your music on Amazon Cloud...GET AN iPOD! (no, not iPAD, iPOD).  Also, you can download books and music from your Cloud Drive to read or listen to when you know you will not have WiFi access.  You can just remove them later from the device once you don't need them.  They will still be stored for you on your cloud drive.  OK, so you may not be able to sit on a plane and watch your favorite film, but considering airlines now have a ton of channels to view on their flights, I can live without Netflix for a few hours.  Again, this is NOT an iPAD, folks!  You knew this from the start, so don't start complaining now that is does not do what an iPAD does.  Just spend more money and get one instead!For those others that complained...the Amazon Silk only works as fast as YOUR WiFi connection. That is pretty much the same with any WiFi device, by the way.  Apps are a little limited, but in just one day I have noticed a huge increase in what is available.  I am sure more are on the way.  Give the Kindle Fire time to breathe and it will improve with every update, otherwise wait a year before buying it.  If you did buy it and are complaining, give yourself a week or so before jumping to return it, because I can almost guarantee you in a week, those things won't bother you anymore.  Unless, of course, you got a defective machine, which can and does happen, then by all means, get a new one. But, please make sure IT IS defective, because reading over those one star reviews I saw many which were user issues, not the Kindle's.And maybe I was lucky and got one that is not defective, but I see thus far at least 440 others got a good one, too judging by the 5 star reviews.  I suggest those who don't like it because of their own limitations, skip the one star reviews and be fair to the rest of us who may be easier to please.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

