 this feature because I have a life, and don't need to have movies and tv shows wherever I am.  You know what else I like?  I like the size.  I know that one of the main reasons that people like to sharpshoot at this device (and others like it) is the lack of a 10 inch screen, but for me, the smaller size is exactly what makes this tool (yes, tool, not toy) ideal, is the fact that at need, I can just stick it in my cargo pocket.As I said earlier, I'm not a techie, so the dpi and megapixels and what have you don't mean much to me.  Likewise, the lack of forward or rear facing cameras mean nothing to me, as the phone in my pocket has a more than adequate camera. Seriously, who uses a 10 inch tablet to take pictures? Well, there is that guy I saw doing eaxactly that at Disney World this past summer, but I doubt that many people do it.  I am not going to use the Kindle Fire (or the Ipad or any other tablet) to "create content" (whatever the heck that means) which I suspect is the case for most consumers of these products.No, what I really want to do with it is to read my kindle content on a device with which I can browse the web, blog, text, and send/recieve email on the go.  I don't need to spend $500 dollars to do those things.... and I don't need to have a dataplan.Look, I admit that as a Kindle owner and long-time Amazon consumer, I am somewhat biased, but if your tablet usage is anything like mine, this is the device for you.  Don't pay for stuff that you don't want, and aren't likely to use, simply because it is trendy.The Kindle Fire is a smokin' hot product, and I suspect that you would be really happy with it.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

