3 of 3 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsThe perfect device for my needs.,November 16, 2011By&nbsp;P.N.(NYC)  -See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Finally a tablet that has everything I want, and none of the things I don't need, at a great price. Things like cameras, GPS, etc. I never wanted a tablet for those things--I have those things where I want them: on my phone, in my pocket. If that's what you're looking for in a tablet, then Fire is obviously not the right device for you.The Fire is a breeze to set up. Once I was up and running, it was such a great feeling to see all of my books already there waiting for me, all of the TV shows I've ever purchased waiting for me in the video library, etc. Amazon just does cloud syncing better than anyone--it's as simple as that.The carousel keeps the most recent items you've used near the front, and you can also use the search bar to search for something on the device. You can add things to your favorites list just beneath the carousel.Videos look great--sharp and clear with amazing colors. Reading comics with the comiXology app is a real pleasure--I haven't read comics in years but I've already enjoyed a couple titles with the comiXology app, and I'll definitely continue to use it. I love having all my Amazon music there for streaming and/or downloading.Yes, the device only comes with 8GB internal storage, but because all of your Amazon media exists in the cloud and can be streamed, 8GB is more than enough. I ride the subway daily so I imagine I will download some things to the device so I can read/listen/watch them while I'm offline on my commute, but then those things can be deleted when I'm done with them or want to switch them for something else. And the best part is that they'll always be in the cloud if I ever need them again.The size of the Fire is PERFECT. To me 10" tablets are so cumbersome, especially when trying to use them while commuting. I see people on the train all the time readjusting, trying to find a way to hold their big tablets that is comfortable! The Fire always feels comfortable, whether holding in one hand or two. I love that I can slip it into my backpack without it taking up much space or adding much weight.I linked the email client to my main personal account, and though I didn't buy the Fire so much for that purpose, it's nice having it there if I want it. It was very easy to set up and looks great. The web browser is functional, and though I didn't notice it being particularly fast, I think the browser must become quicker with use as it begins to be able to predict your browsing habits, etc.The build of this tablet is really great. It feels very solid and high quality in your hands. As Amazon has said time and time again, it's designed to essentially disappear and not get in the way of your experience with books, movies, apps, etc. Mission accomplished, Amazon. It's a very well designed piece of hardware.Regarding Prime membership, I was already a Prime member so the Fire seems especially suited to someone like me. For those of you on the fence about it, let me just say that Prime membership is worth every penny, and Amazon continues to make Prime membership more and more valuable as they fold more perks into it (without raising its cost!). The ability to stream a selection of movies and TV at no cost, the ability to borrow a selection of Kindle books at no cost, and of course the ever popular 2 day shipping. This may ultimately be the thing that sways people one way or the other. Prime membership is not necessary to enjoy the Fire, but it certainly makes it MORE enjoyable/usable/etc.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

