3 of 3 people found the following review helpful5.0 out of 5 starsAmazing little device,November 16, 2011By&nbsp;M. Miller "middaleman"(Louisville, KY)  -See all my reviews(REAL NAME)&nbsp;&nbsp;Amazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Ok, two things first off.1) This is not an iPad.  It is also less than half the price of an iPad.  If you want to edit or create content, get an iPad.  If you're an Apple fanboi, get an iPad.  This device has a specific market (content consumers, and specifically Amazon content consumers) and I am it.2) People who posted their reviews before the 15th did not have a device in hand. Even some of the people who reviewed it after have never used it.  Don't review a device you've never used.  That's stupid.  Also, why do people give a PRODUCT a bad review because they are unhappy with Amazon's policies?  One has nothing to do with the other.  Stop it.Having said that, this is an amazing little tablet.  Movies stream flawlessly (I've tried Prime, Netflix and Hulu+), books work just like the Kindle Reader on any other tablet, music plays fine (the players are all easy to use and the interfaces very intuitive) and there are more than enough Apps to keep most people happy.  Obviously that will continue to grow.  The Amazon app store has always focused on quality over quantity.  You don't have to sort through the trash like you do in the Google store.Yes, the power button is not in an ideal place.  I've hit it accidentally a couple of times (pops up a message which is easy to get rid of).  Sound quality on the device itself is so so, but I have a nice set of ear buds which sound GREAT.  The software is obviously a 1.0 release.  Occasional lag, and not registering a touch do happen.  I've not yet used a new device that didn't have bugs in it's initial release.  The iPad is on it's 2nd version of hardware and 5th major software release, so yes, it's interface is smoother in use (though I think not in design).  I'm sure with the massive sales of this device there will be plenty of software updates and the App catalog will grow exponentially.  The hardware is there to make it happen.If you are an Amazon customer and consumer of Amazon content this device is almost a no brainer.  Stop reading reviews and order one now.  (Though don't throw out your e-Ink Kindle.  This thing won't work as well outdoors or for hours long reading sessions.  The screen is pretty glossy and honestly there is just no replacing e-Ink for hard core reading). If you are looking at this as an alternative to the iPad (or even another Android tablet) then consider that the Fire will do 80% of what you want to do on those devices (honestly 99% of what you will do frequently) and cost you 60% less.  You could buy 2 of these and a Kindle Touch for the price of an iPad.  Also consider if you want to buy into Amazon's ecosystem.  Just like with Apple, the glory of the device is how well it integrates into that content.  Being a Prime member is almost mandatory to get the full benefit, but it's $20 a year less than Netflix for basically the same streaming service plus 2 day shipping and the book library.  Add a Roku streaming device to your TV (available from Amazon) and you can watch all of your Prime content and Amazon purchase or rented movies on your TV set.  If you aren't into Amazon and have $500 burning a hole in your pocket... go with the iPad.  It's a fine device.  If you are into Amazon and prefer not to over pay for things, get a Fire.  It is an equally fine device.  Just different.Last night I was sitting in bed watching Transformers: Dark of the Moon on my Fire when I realized I had a 42" TV sitting a few feet away.  I paused the movie, turned on the TV, brought up the Roku, went to my Amazon content and resumed the movie right where I had paused it, then proceeded to play Cut the Rope on the Fire, pausing it when big robots started blowing stuff up because really, is there any need to keep up with the "story" in a Michael Bay movie?  Yeah, I don't think so either.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

