3 of 3 people found the following review helpful4.0 out of 5 starsSolid, worth the money,November 15, 2011By&nbsp;mjs-See all my reviewsAmazon Verified Purchase(What's this?)This review is from:Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-Fi (Electronics)Kindle Fire, Full Color 7" Multi-touch Display, Wi-FiThe Kindle Fire was something that intrigued me as soon as it was announced. I currently have an iPad 2 and have had an iPad as well. I have had a xoom, samsung 10.1 as well. While the Xoom and Samsung all fell short of what I was wanting in a tablet, the iPad always met my expectations.The Kindle Fire is NOT an iPad killer. I don't believe it was ever intended to be. One is a 7 inch tablet, while the other is a 9.7 inch tablet. Completely different tablets going after different markets.The Fire is more of a cloud based tablet, while the iPad is more on storage device. Neither is right or wrong, better or worse. That is a users choice.Right when I got the package and opened it up I felt a very solid quality product. It did not feel cheap like the Xoom and Samsung. The back is a hard rubber type material instead of a cheap plastic. It feels like a tank to be honest for it's size.So I turned it on and connected to the internet, downloaded an update right away (seemed pretty big), updated the Fire, then connected my account (comes connected to my amazon account) to amazon.The screen is very solid. It is as good as any screen I have seen, that includes the iPad. Colors are rich, yet not over saturated. Pictures I put onto the device look as good as they do on my computer screen.The UI was responsive and I love that Amazon specialized it for their device. I wish more of the "other" tablets would do that like Apple has done with the iPad. It really feels like the OS was made for this device.It is very easy to navigate between apps, web, books, etc... Zero complaints about it. It loads quick but does have a little bit of lag when scrolling side to side, up and down. If you are new to the tablets, you will probably not even notice it. It isn't something huge, just something that you can notice a little.I loaded up Hulu+, Netflix and Amazon Prime and all three looked great on the screen. With my quick connection it loaded just fine.I uploaded a video onto the device using the USB to see if it would play it, it did. It was a m4v file which plays on apple devices. Again the screen was solid , zero complaints. It can also play mp4 files as well. Will test more files formats as I go or find on the web.Only thing I wish you could do is access the video folder, picture folder and document folder on my amazon cloud drive. Maybe I am missing something but I can't access it from the Kindle Fire. I uploaded a video onto there a while back anticipating it would be able to see it. No go, but again maybe I am missing something here.Uploading a video from computer to kindle is slow. Talking 3 to 5 MB/sec over USB. Very slow for devices these days. But again this device is really selling the cloud, not actual files on the device.Facebook app is no app, it is a link to the mobile site for facebok. Very disappointed in that fact. Especially when Amazon said it was a app. Hopefully they will get an actual app like other tablets. Not just a link to their mobile site.I uploaded my music files to the cloud (over 2000 m4a files) and they play just fine as well as mp3. Their website gives you a list of compatible files.I also was able to go to my local library system here in Utah and download ebooks to the Kindle Fire as well. My system allows a total of 10 books out at a time. With the Prime membership you also get a Loan book, which gives you one a month. It resets every 1st of the month.There are just so many positives with this very affordable device. The negatives are there though.The negatives I see is again no access to my cloud drive. I might be missing something so hopefully I am wrong.Screen is only 7 inches and when viewing vertical it is okay on certain apps, but when on a web page that isn't mobile friendly the text is very small. When viewing horizontal there is not a ton of real estate. So scrolling becomes your enemy.Apps apps apps, in time I believe developers will come over to build for the Fire. I believe that the Fire is different than other tablets in that it has a unique UI which really does set itself apart from other android tablets. Plus I really do believe Amazon is going to kill with the tablet, but as of right now, apps are in the thousands, but lets be honest here only a few are really useful.I have not had a chance to test the battery out yet. But from what I have read online it gets what they have estimated.I really can't think of anything else. It is a fantastic buy I believe for the money. It is no iPad killer because it isn't competing with the iPad. It is a completely different tablet going after a different market of people.I like the idea of cloud based, just wish it was 16GB instead of 8GB. That way if and when you know wifi is not going to be an option (while traveling) you have space to put what you need onto the device.Right now I am testing different file compresions and sizes to get the most out of movie files without taking up a bunch of space.I either have to do that or invest in a 4G device that can stream at a solid speed. Which I really do not want to do.Overall I would give this thing a 7 out of 10. I believe it does a great job of delivering a fun experience, but falls short in storage. I don't need a camera, or bluetooth or GPS. That is what I have a phone for, thank you apple.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

