 menu at the bottom of each page is intuitive so I got the hang of it quickly.  It can be hidden (by selecting the full-screen option), to create more real estate.So far the only complaint I have is the screen glare (but I also have that problem with the Nook). Since I primarily use my Kindle indoors, it's easy to avoid glare and anti-glare screens can be bought, if needed. However the issue doesn't bother me.Kindle Fire does offer Cloud storage, but no SD card slot, so that could be a problem for some. The Kindle's native memory is fine for my purposes.One of the nicest perks about owning Kindle Fire is the huge number of apps and books available to download.  You can either take advantage of both free and pay apps and Kindle books on Amazon, get them from many sites online, or download library ebooks if your library supports that.  Kindle Fire is also compatible with MP3 music and audiobooks.The Kindle Fire is a wonderful tablet and I wouldn't hesitate to recommend it to anyone who wants about 90% of Ipad's functionality at a fraction of the cost. Kindle Fire is my new favorite tech toy.Help other customers find the most helpful reviews&nbsp;Was this review helpful to you?&nbsp;YesNoReport abuse|PermalinkComment&nbsp;Comment

