device. But then, you can buy one for every family member and still get a good amount of features for your money. That's why you're reading these reviews - right?12. Solid construction.13. Very intuitive. Learning curve on a Kindle is pretty quick.Cons -1. Sound stinks. The speakers are small and tinny sounding. Now a good set of headsets here makes a big difference.2. Silk browser is ok. 3rd party browsers might give you a better experience in some cases. I use the Silk Browser, and also use 3rd party browsers for various reasons.3. Video playback of mp4's are ok with the stock player, but can be improved with 3rd party applications.4. NO bluetooth, or ethernet.  WiFi or USB connectivity only. It's not a show stopper, but it does require mention as a "con" feature.5. Power button placement makes it easy to bump the switch when you're in portrait mode. Of course adding a protective skin or case, usually fixes this.6. Battery... I haven't changed one, but it looks like a factory thing at this point.. Take my comment here lightly since I haven't researched it at the time I wrote this.7. Applications - Applications are still limited however considering that the Kindle released in November 2011, I've seen the applications list grow considerably. Many Android apps will work on a Kindle Fire.8. Limited documentation. The Kindle manual is actually on the Kindle itself. Make sure you a have a Kindle savy user around when you first open the box.Special Note - Amazon Prime. Amazon Prime is the service that gives you streaming, free shipping, and other discounts when shopping on Amazon. Currently the cost is $79 and it's a pretty good deal when you consider, that not only can you stream from your kindle, you can stream from your laptop as well. Shoppers will also like the free shipping offered by most sellers if you're an Amazon Prime member. It's not a NetFlix yet... but movie selections keeps growing every day.Finally, As I mentioned earlier, I like the Kindle Fire. It gets 